ess | location = Austin, Texas, USA}}\n* Rees, Laurence. ''Horror in the East'', published 2001 by the British Broadcasting Company\n* Seagrave, Sterling & Peggy. ''Gold warriors: America's secret recovery of Yamashita's gold, Verso Books, 2003. {{ISBN|1-85984-542-8}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Sherman | first = Christine | authorlink = | year = 2001 | title = War Crimes: International Military Tribunal | publisher = Turner Publishing Company | location = | isbn = 1-56311-728-2}}-Detailed account of the [[International Military Tribunal for the Far East]] proceedings in Tokyo\n* Trefalt, Beatrice . \"Japanese War Criminals in Indochina and the French Pursuit of Justice: Local and International Constraints.\" ''Journal of Contemporary History'' 49.4 (2014): 727-742.\n* {{Cite book | last = Tsurumi | first = Kazuko | authorlink =  | year = 1970 | title = Social change and the individual: Japan before and after defeat in World War II | publisher = Princeton University Press | location = Princeton, USA | isbn = 0-691-09347-4 | url = https://archive.org/details/socialchangeindi0000tsur }}\n* Williams, Peter. ''Unit 731: Japan's Secret Biological Warfare in World War II'', Free Press, 1989. {{ISBN|0-02-935301-7}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Wilson | first = Sandra|display-authors=etal | authorlink = | year = 2017 | title = Japanese War Criminals: The Politics of Justice After the Second World War | publisher = Columbia University Press | location = New York, USA | isbn = 9780231179225}}\n* {{Cite book | last = Yamamoto | first = Masahiro | authorlink = | year = 2000 | title = Nanking: Anatomy of an Atrocity | publisher = Praeger Publishers | location = | isbn = 0-275-96904-5}}- A rebuttal to Iris Chang's book on the Nanking massacre.\n{{refend}}\n\n===Audio/visual media===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Minoru Matsui (2001), [http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/east/04/07/japan.devils/index.html ''Japanese Devils''], documentary with interview of veteran soldiers from the Imperial Japanese Army (Japanese ''Devils shed light on a dark past'') CNN\n** [http://www.midnighteye.com/reviews/japdevil.shtml ''Japanese Devils''], Midnight Eye,\n* {{Cite video | people= The History Channel | date= 2000 | url= | title = Japanese War Crimes: Murder Under The Sun | medium = Video documentary (DVD & VHS) | location = | publisher= A & E Home Video}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Please alphabetize according to display title -->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070609112646/http://home.pacbell.net/fbaldie/Battling_Bastards_of_Bataan.html Battling Bastards of Bataan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080113004217/http://www.sjwar.org/ \"Biochemical Warfare \u2013 Unit 731\". Alliance for Preserving the Truth of Sino-Japanese War.] No date.\n* [http://www.warbirdforum.com/cannibal.htm \"Cannibalism\". Dan Ford, \"Japan at War, 1931\u20131945\"] September 2007.\n* [http://www.centurychina.com/wiihist/confess/index.html \"Confessions of Japanese war criminals\".] No date.\n* [https://fas.org/nuke/guide/japan/bw/ \"History of Japan's biological weapons program\"] [[Federation of American Scientists]], 2000-04-16\n* [http://www.systemclub.co.kr/ Ji Man-Won's website (in Korean)] Various dates.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/elsewhere/journalist/story/0,7792,1338296,00.html Justin McCurry, \"Japan's sins of the past\"] in ''[[The Guardian]]'', 2004-10-28\n* [https://www.archives.gov/iwg/ Nazi War Crimes and Japanese Imperial Government Records Interagency Working Group (IWG) ] U.S. [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA). No date.\n* [http://www.skycitygallery.com/japan/japan.html \"The Other Holocaust\"] No date.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041009171355/http://www.kimsoft.com/2002/jp-rape.htm \"Rape of Queen MIN\"] 2002\n* [http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.CHAP3.HTM R.J. Rummel, \"Statistics Of Japanese Democide: Estimates, Calculations, And Sources\" ] [[University of Hawaii]], 2002\n* [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/08/28/1030508070534.html Shane Green. \"The Asian Auschwitz of Unit 731\" ] in ''[[The Age]]'', 2002-08-29\n* [http://www.mofa.go.jp/announce/press/pm/murayama/9508.html \"Statement by Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama\"] 1995-08-15\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.technologyartist.com/unit_731/ |title=Steven Butler, \"A half century of denial: the hidden truth about Japan's unit 731\" |access-date=October 31, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061119053825/http://www.technologyartist.com/unit_731/ |archive-date=November 19, 2006 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }} in ''[[US News & World Report]]'' 1995-07-31\n* [http://histclo.com/essay/war/ww2/pow/pow-jap.html Japanese Treatment of World War II POWs]\n\n{{JapanEmpireNavbox}}\n{{IJA special research units}}\n{{World War II}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Japanese War Crimes}}\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in China]]\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in Korea]]\n[[Category:Historical negationism]]\n[[Category:History of Asia]]\n[[Category:Imperial Japanese Army]]\n[[Category:Imperial Japanese Navy]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Japanese culture]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes| ]]\n[[Category:Military history of Japan]]\n[[Category:War crimes committed by country]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Thier > Their +", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_war_crimes"}
{"title_page": "Cary Elwes", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n | image            = Cary Elwes September 2015.jpg\n | caption          = Elwes in September 2015\n | birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|10|26}}\n | birth_place      = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n | residence        = <!--[[Los Angeles]], [[California (state)|California]], U.S.-->\n | birth_name       = Ivan Simon Cary Elwes\n | occupation       = Actor, writer\n | years_active     = 1979\u2013present\n | alma_mater = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n | parents          = [[Dominick Elwes]]<br/>[[Tessa Kennedy]]\n | relatives        = [[Cassian Elwes]] (brother)<br> [[Damian Elwes]] (brother)\n | spouse           = {{marriage|Lisa Marie Kurbikoff|2000}} \n | children         = 1}}\n\n'''Ivan Simon Cary Elwes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|l|w|\u026a|s}}; born 26 October 1962)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2008/10/26/The_almanac/UPI-34121225006200|title=The Almanac|publisher=UPI|date=26 October 2008|accessdate=29 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=World Almanac|work=[[Kent County Daily Times]]|date=26 October 2010|quote=Today's Birthdays: Cary Elwes}}</ref> is an English-American actor and writer.<ref name=\"thewrap.com\">{{cite news|last1=Reilly|first1=Travis|title=Colin Hanks, Johnny Knoxville, Alex Pettyfer Added to 'Elvis & Nixon'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/colin-hanks-johnny-knoxville-alex-pettyfer-added-to-elvis-nixon/|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=16 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2014-11-02/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 November 2014|language=en}}</ref> He is best known for his leading film roles as Westley in ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'' (1987), [[Robin Hood]] in ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]'' (1993), and [[Dr. Lawrence Gordon]] in the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' film series]]. He is also known for leading roles in films like ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' (1991), and ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' (1994), as well as supporting roles in films including ''[[Days of Thunder]]'' (1990), ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'' (1996), ''[[Kiss the Girls (1997 film)|Kiss the Girls]]'' (1997), ''[[Liar Liar]]'' (1997), Michael Collins in ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (1998), ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]'' (1999), ''[[Shadow of the Vampire]]'' (2000), ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' (2001), ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]'' (2004), ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'' (2009), and ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=caryelwes.htm|title=Cary Elwes Movie Box Office Results|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref> He has had recurring roles in television series including ''[[The X-Files]]'', ''[[Psych]]'', and ''[[Stranger Things (season 3)|Stranger Things]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/02/arts/television/stranger-things-netflix-cary-elwes.html|title='Stranger Things': Cary Elwes Lives It Up As a Shady Mayor|first=Brian|last=Tallerico|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He joined the third season of ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'' as Gavin Hawk, a famed [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/marvelous-mrs-maisel-season-3-cary-elwes-stephanie-hsu-1203229363/|first=Joe|last=Otterson| title='Marvelous Mrs. Maisel' Season 3 Adds Cary Elwes, Stephanie Hsu (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=30 May 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nIvan Simon Cary Elwes was born on 26 October 1962 in [[Westminster|Westminster, London]], the youngest of three sons of portrait painter [[Dominic Elwes]]<ref name=\"People1995\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105004,00.html |title=A Hero to the Hilt |last=Cerio |first=Gregory |volume=43 |work=[[People (American magazine)|People]] |date=6 February 1995 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110330190839/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105004,00.html |archivedate=30 March 2011 |url-status=live |issue=5 |df=dmy }}</ref> and interior designer and socialite [[Tessa Kennedy]]. He is the brother of artist [[Damian Elwes]]<ref name=\"Chicago1990\"/> and film producer [[Cassian Elwes]]. His stepfather, [[Elliott Kastner]], was an American film producer.<ref name=\"People1995\"/> His paternal grandfather was painter [[Simon Elwes]],<ref name=\"Chicago1990\">{{cite news|first=Jae-Ha|last=Kim|title=British actor takes turn as American in 'Glory'|page=25|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=12 January 1990}}</ref> whose own father was the diplomat and tenor [[Gervase Elwes]] (1866\u20131921).<ref>{{cite book|title=Loose Canon: A Portrait of Brian Brindley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=At3vy0eh2LUC&pg=PA134&dq=Gervase+Elwes+Simon#v=onepage&q=Gervase%20Elwes%20Simon&f=false|last=Thompson|first=Damian|authorlink=Damian Thompson|page=134|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]]|isbn=0-8264-7418-7|date=22 June 2004}}</ref> His other great-grandfathers include the diplomat [[Rennell Rodd, 1st Baron Rennell]] and industrialist [[Ivan Rikard Ivanovi\u0107]]. Elwes has  [[English people|English]], [[Irish people|Irish]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], [[History of the Jews in Croatia|Croatian Jewish]], and [[Serbs|Serbian]] ancestry,<ref>90265 Malibu Life & Style Magazine Issue No. 2; Fall 2013</ref> the latter two from his maternal grandmother, Da\u0161ka McLean, whose second husband, [[Neil McLean (politician)|Billy McLean]], was an operative for [[Special Operations Executive]] during [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patrickleighfermor.org/2010/07/01/one-mans-great-game-lieutenant-colonel-%E2%80%9Cbilly%E2%80%9D-mclean/|title=One Man\u2019s Great Game: Lieutenant Colonel \"Billy\" McLean - Patrick Leigh Fermor|work=Patrick Leigh Fermor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soetrails.wordpress.com/tag/billy-mclean/page/2/|title=Billy McLean - S.O.E. Trails|first=Billy|last=McLean|date=4 March 2013|publisher=S.O.E. Trails}}</ref>\n\nOne of Elwes's relatives is [[John Elwes (politician)|John Elwes]], who was believed to be the inspiration for [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] in ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' (1843), having been referenced by [[Charles Dickens]] himself in chapter six of his last completed novel, ''[[Our Mutual Friend]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.literaturepage.com/read/dickens-our-mutual-friend-577.html||first=Michael| last=Moncur|publisher=The Literature Page|title=Charles Dickens: Our Mutual Friend}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/only-in-britain/man-who-inspired-ebenezer-scrooge/|title=John Elwes: scrimper who inspired Ebenezer Scrooge|first=Norman|last=Miller|date=20 September 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> Elwes himself played five roles in the [[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|2009 film adaptation]] of ''A Christmas Carol''. Through his maternal grandfather, Elwes is also related to [[Alexander Kennedy|Sir Alexander William \"Blackie\" Kennedy]], one of the first photographers to document the archaeological site of [[Petra]] following the collapse of the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.genealogy.com/forum/surnames/topics/kennedy/658/|title=Sir Alexander Blackie William| publisher= Genealogy.com}}</ref>\n\nElwes was brought up as a [[Roman Catholic]] and was an [[altar boy]] at [[Westminster Cathedral]], although he did not attend [[denominational]] schools as most of the men on his father's side of the family had, including his father.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guthrie |first=Marisa |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2005/12/04/2005-12-04_the_spirit_moved_him.html |title=The spirit moved him |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |quote=Elwes, who grew up a Catholic... |date=4 December 2005 |accessdate=13 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61zzNYuVF?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2005-12-04/entertainment/18305424_1_vatican-residence-pope-john-paul-ii-papal |archivedate=27 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> His paternal relatives include such [[clerics]] as [[Dudley Charles Cary-Elwes]] (1868\u20131932), the [[Roman Catholic]] [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Northampton|Bishop of Northampton]], Abbott [[Columba Cary-Elwes]] ([[Ampleforth Abbey]], [[Saint Louis Abbey]]), and Father Luke Cary-Elwes ([[Fort Augustus Abbey]]). He discussed this in an interview while he was filming the 2005 [[CBS]] television film ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]'', in which he played the young priest [[Karol Wojty\u0142a]].\n\nElwes's parents divorced when he was four years old. In 1975, when Elwes was 13, his father died by suicide. He was educated at [[Harrow School]],<ref name=\"Chicago1990\"/> and the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]].<ref name=\"StraitsTimes\">{{cite journal|title=Dr Gordon is back in Saw \u2013 Cary Elwes's character from the first Saw film is back by popular demand|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=5 January 2011}}</ref> In 1981, he moved to the United States to study acting at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[Bronxville, New York]].<ref name=\"Chronicle1993\">{{cite journal|title=The 'Robin' Who Has Sherwood Forest Chuckling|last=Tam Jr|first=Henry|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|page=C6|date=13 August 1993}}</ref> While living there, Elwes studied acting at both the [[Actors Studio]]<ref name=\"Chronicle1993\"/> and the [[Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute]] under the tutelage of [[Al Pacino]]'s mentor, Charlie Laughton (not to be confused with English actor [[Charles Laughton]]).<ref name=\"StraitsTimes\"/> As a teenager, he also worked as a production assistant on the films ''[[Absolution (1978 film)|Absolution]]'', ''[[Octopussy]]'', and ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'', where he was assigned to [[Marlon Brando]]. When Elwes introduced himself to the famous actor, Brando insisted on calling him \"Rocky\" after [[Rocky Marciano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q2yqE_QYanU|title=Mark & Brian w/Cary Elwes on Marlon Brando|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=8 May 2008|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Film ===\nElwes made his acting [[:wikt:debut|debut]] in 1984 with [[Marek Kanievska]]'s film ''[[Another Country (film)|Another Country]]'', which was loosely based on the English [[boarding school]] exploits of British spies, [[Guy Burgess|Burgess]], [[Kim Philby|Philby]] and [[Donald Maclean (spy)|MacLean]]. He played James Harcourt, a gay student.<ref name=\"Chicago1990\"/> He went on to play [[Guilford Dudley]] in the British historical drama film ''[[Lady Jane (1986 film)|Lady Jane]]'', opposite [[Helena Bonham Carter]]. He was then cast as a stable-boy-turned-swashbuckler Westley in [[Rob Reiner]]'s fantasy-comedy ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'', which was based on the [[The Princess Bride (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[William Goldman]]. It was a modest box office success,<ref name=\"Bride\">{{cite journal|title='The Princess Bride' Turns 20|journal=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|page=6J|last=Gray Streeter|first=Leslie|date=9 December 2007|quote=[w]as a modest hit. But it became a raging cult classic after being released on video and shown on cable.}}</ref> but received critical acclaim, earning a score of 97% on the review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/princess_bride|title=The Princess Bride (1987)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> Since being released on home video and television, the film has become a [[cult film|cult classic]].<ref name=\"Bride\"/>\n\n{{Quote|Initially the studio didn't know how to market it. Was it an adventure? A fantasy? A comedy? A romance? A kid's movie? In the end they sold it as a kid's movie and it largely had to rely on word of mouth ... people tell me they still have their [[VHS]] copy that has been passed down from one generation to the next.|Interview from the film's DVD release in 2001<ref>{{cite news |title='Bride' basks in glow of video|work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |last=Westbrook|first=Bruce|date=6 September 2001}}</ref>}}\n\nElwes continued to work steadily, varying between dramatic roles, such as in the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), and comedic roles, as in ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' (1991). In 1993, he starred as [[Robin Hood]] in [[Mel Brooks]]'s comedy, ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]''. Elwes then appeared in supporting roles in such films as [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s adaptation of ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]'', ''[[The Crush (1993 film)|The Crush]]'', ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' (1994), ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'', ''[[Liar Liar]]'', and ''[[Kiss the Girls (1997 film)|Kiss the Girls]]''. In 1999, he portrayed famed theatre and film producer [[John Houseman]] for [[Tim Robbins]] in his ensemble film based on [[Orson Welles]]'s musical, ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]''. Following that, he travelled to [[Luxembourg]] to work with [[John Malkovich]] and [[Willem Dafoe]] in ''[[Shadow of the Vampire]]''. In 2001, he co-starred in [[Peter Bogdanovich]]'s ensemble film ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' portraying movie mogul [[Thomas H. Ince|Thomas Ince]], who died mysteriously while vacationing with [[William Randolph Hearst]] on his [[yacht]].\n\nIn 2004, Elwes starred in the [[Horror film|horror]]\u2013[[Thriller film|thriller]] ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' which, at a budget of a little over $1&nbsp;million, grossed over $100&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"SawBOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw.htm|title=Saw (2004) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref> The same year he appeared in ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]'', this time as the villain, not the hero. He made an uncredited appearance as [[Samuel Adams Green|Sam Green]], the man who introduced [[Andy Warhol]] to [[Edie Sedgwick]], in the 2006 film ''[[Factory Girl (2006 film)|Factory Girl]]''. In 2007, he appeared in [[Garry Marshall]]'s ''[[Georgia Rule]]'' opposite [[Jane Fonda]].\n\nIn 2010, he returned to the ''Saw'' franchise in ''[[Saw 3D]]'' (2010), the seventh film in the series, as Dr. [[Lawrence Gordon (character)|Lawrence Gordon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19954/ |title=Cary Elwes Confirmed for 'Saw 3D', Full Synopsis and Cast |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |date=25 April 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2010 |archivedate=26 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426192519/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19954 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2011, he was selected by [[Ivan Reitman]] to star alongside [[Natalie Portman]] in ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]''. That same year, Elwes and [[Garry Marshall]] teamed up again in the ensemble romantic comedy ''New Year's Eve'' opposite [[Robert de Niro]] and [[Halle Berry]].\n\nIn 2012, Elwes starred in the independent drama ''[[The Citizen (film)|The Citizen]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118039848 |title=4 thesps apply for 'The Citizen' |last=Sneider |first=Jeff |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820004206/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118039848 |archivedate=20 August 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> and the following year Elwes joined [[Selena Gomez]] for the comedy ensemble, ''[[Behaving Badly (film)|Behaving Badly]]'' directed by Tim Garrick. In 2014, he starred in [[John Herzfeld]]'s ensemble comedy ''[[Reach Me]]''. In 2015, he completed four movies: the ensemble drama ''[[Sugar Mountain (film)|Sugar Mountain]]'' directed by Richard Gray; and the dramas ''[[H8RZ]]'', directed by Derrick Borte, ''[[We Don't Belong Here (film)|We Don't Belong Here]]'', opposite [[Anton Yelchin]] and [[Catherine Keener]] directed by Peer Pedersen, and ''[[Being Charlie]]'' which reunited Elwes with director [[Rob Reiner]] after 28 years and premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]].\n\nIn January 2016, Elwes portrayed [[Andy Warhol]] opposite [[Kevin Spacey]] in ''[[Billionaire Boys Club (2016 film)|The Billionaire Boys Club]]'' directed by [[James Cox (director)|James Cox]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/these-upcoming-kevin-spacey-movies-shows-may-be-in-trouble-now.html/?a=viewall|title=These Upcoming Kevin Spacey Projects May Be in Trouble Now|date=1 December 2017|work=The Cheat Sheet|access-date=10 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\nElwes made his first television appearance in 1996 as David Lookner on ''[[Seinfeld]]''. Two years later he played astronaut [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]] in the [[Golden Globe Award]]-winning [[HBO]] [[miniseries]] ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth To the Moon]]''. The following year Elwes was nominated for a [[Golden Satellite Award]] for Best Performance by an Actor in a Mini-Series or Motion Picture Made for Television for his portrayal of Colonel [[James G. Burton|James Burton]] in ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]'' directed by [[Richard Benjamin]]. In 1999, he guest starred as Dr. John York in an episode of the television series ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''. Shortly afterward he received another [[Golden Satellite Award]] nomination for his work on the ensemble NBC Television movie ''[[Uprising (2001 film)|Uprising]]'' opposite [[Jon Voight]] directed by [[Jon Avnet]]. Elwes had a recurring role in the final season (from 2001 to 2002) of [[Chris Carter (screenwriter)|Chris Carter]]'s hit series ''[[The X-Files]]'' as [[FBI Assistant Director]] [[Brad Follmer]].\n\nIn 2004, he portrayed serial killer [[Ted Bundy]] in the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E Network]] film ''The Riverman'', which became one of the highest rated original movies in the network's history and garnered a prestigious [[Banff World Media Festival|BANFF Rockie Award]] nomination. The following year, Elwes played the young [[Pope John Paul II|Karol Wojty\u0142a]] in the [[CBS]] television film ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]'', his second time working with [[Jon Voight]]. The TV film was highly successful not only in North America but also in Europe, where it broke box office records in the late Pope's native [[Poland]] and became the first film ever to break $1&nbsp;million (GBP 739,075.00 current) in three days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pope Picture Breaks Box Office Records|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/pope%20picture%20breaks%20box%20office%20records%20in%20poland_09_03_2006|publisher=contactmusic.com|date=3 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he made a guest appearance on the ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' episode \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep14|Dependent]]\" as a [[Mafia]] lawyer. In 2009, he played the role of [[Pierre Despereaux]], an international art thief, in the fourth-season premiere of ''[[Psych]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35164/first-two-teaser-clips-psych-9 |title=First Two Teaser Clips Psych: 9 |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |date=2 January 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102224255/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35164/first-two-teaser-clips-psych-9 |archivedate=2 November 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2010, he returned to ''[[Psych]]'', reprising his role in the second half of the [[Psych (season 5)|fifth season]], again in the show's [[Psych (season 6)|sixth season]], and again in the show's [[Psych (season 8)|eighth season]] premiere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/07/psych-spoiler-video-season-6-james-roday-dule-hill |title=Psych First Look: The Season 6 Scene Everyone Will Be Talking About! Plus, Musical Update! |last=Slezak |first=Michael |work=TVLine |date=21 July 2011 |accessdate=27 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923042810/http://www.tvline.com/2011/07/psych-spoiler-video-season-6-james-roday-dule-hill/ |archivedate=23 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2014 Elwes played Hugh Ashmeade, Director of the [[CIA]], in the second season of the BYUtv series ''[[Granite Flats]]''.\n\nIn May 2015, Elwes was cast as a series regular in [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]]'s first streaming network series drama, ''[[The Art of More]]'', which explores the cutthroat world of premium auction houses. He played Arthur Davenport, a shrewd and eccentric world-class collector of illegal art and antiquities. The series debuted on 19 November and was picked up for a second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/cary-elwes-cast-the-art-of-more-drama-series-crackle-1201420939/|title=Cary Elwes Joins \u2018The Art Of More\u2019 Drama Series On Crackle|first=Denise|last=Petski|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 Elwes was cast as Larry Kline, Mayor of Hawkins, for the third season of the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Stranger Things]]'', which premiered in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/stranger-things-s3-casting-announcement|title=Stranger Things S3 Casting Announcement|work=[[Netflix]]|language=en|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref> In May 2019, it was announced that he would be joining the third season of the [[Amazon Studios|Amazon]] series ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'' as Gavin Hawk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/05/cary-elwes-marvelous-mrs-maisel-season-3|title=Cary Elwes and His Smoldering Eyes Are Joining Marvelous Mrs. Maisel Season 3|first=Kevin|last=Fitzpatrick|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Voice-over work ===\nElwes's [[voice-over]] work includes the narrator in [[James Patterson]]'s [[audiobook]] ''[[The Jester (novel)|The Jester]]'',<ref>{{cite book|title=The Jester|last=Paterson|first=James|authorlink=James Patterson|last2=Gross|first2=Andrew|authorlink2=Andrew Gross|isbn=1-58621-535-3|publisher=[[Hachette Audio]]| edition=Abridged|date=1 March 2003}}</ref> as well as characters in film and [[television animation]]s such as ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'', ''[[Pinky and The Brain]]'', ''[[Batman Beyond]]'', and the English versions of the [[Studio Ghibli]] films, ''[[Porco Rosso]]'', ''[[Whisper of the Heart (film)|Whisper of the Heart]]'' and ''[[The Cat Returns]]''. For the 2004 video game ''[[The Bard's Tale (2004)|The Bard's Tale]]'', he served as screenwriter, improviser, and voice actor of the main character The Bard. In 2009, Elwes reunited with [[Jason Alexander]] for the [[Indian film]], ''[[Delhi Safari]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2011/05/30/15833/index.html |title=Delhi Safari to feature voice over by Vanessa Williams and Jason Alexander |work=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |date=30 May 2011 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904200314/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2011/05/30/15833/index.html |archivedate=4 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The following year Elwes portrayed the part of Gremlin Gus in Disney's video game, ''[[Epic Mickey 2: The Power of Two]]''. In 2014, he appeared in ''[[Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey]]'' as the voice of scientists [[Edmond Halley]] and [[Robert Hooke]].\n\n=== Motion capture work ===\nIn 2009 Elwes joined the cast of [[Robert Zemeckis]]'s [[motion capture]] adaptation of [[Charles Dickens]]' ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'' portraying five roles. That same year he was chosen by [[Steven Spielberg]] to appear in his [[motion capture]] adaptation of Belgian artist [[Herg\u00e9]]'s popular comic strip ''[[The Adventures of Tintin: The Secret of the Unicorn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a347079/the-adventures-of-tintin-premieres-in-london-pictures.html#~p5ZywC1hHstyq3|title='The Adventures of Tintin' premieres in London \u2013 Pictures|work=Digital Spy}}</ref>\n\n=== Theatre ===\nIn 2003 Elwes portrayed [[Kerry Max Cook]] in the [[off-Broadway]] play ''[[The Exonerated (play)|The Exonerated]]'' in New York, directed by [[Bob Balaban]] (18\u201323 March 2003).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/78481-Cary-Elwes-and-Brooke-Shields-Join-Off-Broadways-Exonerated-March-18-23 |title=Cary Elwes and Brooke Shields Join Off-Broadway's ''Exonerated'', 18\u201323 March |last=Hernandez |first=Ernio |work=Playbill.com |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=27 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629082056/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/78481-Cary-Elwes-and-Brooke-Shields-Join-Off-Broadways-Exonerated-March-18-23 |archivedate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\nIn October 2014 Touchstone ([[Simon & Schuster]]) published Elwes's memoir of the making of ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'', entitled ''As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride'', which Elwes co-wrote with Joe Layden. The book featured never-before-told stories, exclusive behind-the-scenes photographs, and interviews with co-stars [[Robin Wright]], [[Wallace Shawn]], [[Billy Crystal]], [[Christopher Guest]], [[Fred Savage]] and [[Mandy Patinkin]], as well as author and screenwriter [[William Goldman]], producer [[Norman Lear]], and director [[Rob Reiner]]. The book debuted on ''[[The New York Times Best Seller list]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2014-11-02/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 November 2014|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.geekwithcurves.com/2014/06/cary-elwes-wrote-book-about-princess.html|title=Cary Elwes wrote book about the making of the film, ''The Princess Bride''|publisher= geekwithcurves.com|date=June 2014|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Other projects ===\nIn 2014, Elwes co-wrote the screenplay for a film entitled ''[[Elvis & Nixon]]'', about the pair's famous meeting at the [[White House]] in 1970.<ref name=\"thewrap.com\"/> The film, which starred [[Michael Shannon]] and [[Kevin Spacey]], was bought by [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] as their first theatrical feature and was released on 22 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/amazon-elvis-nixon-kevin-spacey-1201500537/|date=23 June 2015|title=\u2018Elvis & Nixon\u2019 Starring Kevin Spacey Sold to Amazon|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n== Lawsuit ==\nIn August 2005, Elwes filed a lawsuit against [[Evolution Entertainment]], his management firm and producer of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''. Elwes said he was promised a minimum of one percent of the producers' net profits of the film and did not receive the full amount.<ref name=\"Cary\">{{cite news|title=Not everyone happy with their cut from Saw |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/film/not-everyone-happy-with-their-cut-from-saw/2005/08/20/1124435169494.html |last=Mitchell |first=Peter |agency=[[Association of American Publishers|AAP]] |work=[[The Age]] |date=20 August 2005 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107064640/http://www.theage.com.au/news/film/not-everyone-happy-with-their-cut-from-saw/2005/08/20/1124435169494.html |archivedate=7 November 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The case was [[legal settlement|settled out of court]]. In 2010, he reprised his role in ''[[Saw 3D]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fangoria.com/index.php?id=641:saw-vii-synopsis-and-cast-revealedincluding-cary-elwes&option=com_content&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=167 |title=\"Saw VII\" Synopsis and Cast Revealed \u2013 Including Cary Elwes! |last=Gingold |first=Michael |work=[[Fangoria]] |date=25 April 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614095114/http://www.fangoria.com/index.php?id=641:saw-vii-synopsis-and-cast-revealedincluding-cary-elwes&option=com_content&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=167 |archivedate=14 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nElwes met photographer Lisa Marie Kurbikoff in 1991 at a [[Cook-off#Chili cook-off|chili cook-off]] in [[Malibu, California]], and they became engaged in 1997.<ref name=\"Marriage\">{{cite journal|title=Celebrities \u2013 DeGeneres 'Bedding' Talk-Show Guests|work=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|date=3 May 2007|page=D2|quote=Elwes and Lisa Marie (''n\u00e9e'' Kurbikoff) met in 1991 at a Malibu chili cook-off. They were engaged in 1997 and tied the knot three years later.}}</ref> They married in 2000 and have one daughter together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20037158,00.html |title=Cary Elwes, Wife Welcome a Girl |last=Silverman |first=Stephen M. |last2=Jordan |first2=Julie |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=27 April 2007 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107065256/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20037158,00.html |archivedate=7 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" summary=\"List of films and roles\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Yesterday's Hero]]''\n| Disco Dancer\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2| 1984\n| ''[[Another Country (film)|Another Country]]''\n| James Harcourt\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Oxford Blues]]''\n| Lionel\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| data-sort-value=\"Bride, The\"| ''[[The Bride (1985 film)|The Bride]]''\n| Capt. Josef Schoden\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Lady Jane (1986 film)|Lady Jane]]''\n| [[Guilford Dudley]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1987\n| ''[[Maschenka (1987 film)|Maschenka]]''\n| Lev Glebovich Ganin\n| \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Princess Bride, The\"| ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]''\n| Westley / [[Dread Pirate Roberts]]\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Never on Tuesday]]''\n| Tow Truck Driver\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]''\n| Maj. Cabot Forbes\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Days of Thunder]]''\n| Russ Wheeler\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Hot Shots!]]''\n| Lt. Kent Gregory\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1992\n| ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]''\n| Lord [[Arthur Holmwood]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Leather Jackets (film)|Leather Jackets]]''\n| Dobbs\n| Also associate producer\n|-\n| ''[[Porco Rosso]]''\n| Donald Curtis (voice)\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1993\n| ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]''\n| [[Robin Hood]]\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Crush, The\"| ''[[The Crush (1993 film)|The Crush]]''\n| Nick Eliot\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1994\n| data-sort-value=\"Jungle Book, The\"| ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]''\n| Capt. William Boone\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Chase, The\"| ''[[The Chase (1994 film)|The Chase]]''\n| Steve Horsegroovy\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]''\n| Dr. Jonas Miller\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1997\n| ''[[Kiss the Girls (1997 film)|Kiss the Girls]]''\n| Det. Nick Ruskin\n| Nominated \u2013 [[Blockbuster Entertainment Awards]] Best Supporting ActoDet\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Informant, The\"| ''[[The Informant (1997 film)|The Informant]]''\n| Lt. David Ferris\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Liar Liar]]''\n| Jerry\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Quest for Camelot]]''\n| Garrett\n| Voice\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]''\n| Col. James G. Burton\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]''\n| [[John Houseman]]\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Shadow of the Vampire]]''\n| [[Fritz Arno Wagner|Fritz Arno \"Fritzy\" Wagner]]\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| data-sort-value=\"Cat's Meow, The\"| ''[[The Cat's Meow]]''\n| [[Thomas H. Ince]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2002\n| ''[[Wish You Were Dead]]''\n| Mac \"Macbeth\" Wilson\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Comic Book Villains]]''\n| Carter\n| Also co-producer\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Porco Rosso]]''\n| Donald Curtis\n| Voice; English dub\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2004\n| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| Dr. [[Lawrence Gordon (character)|Lawrence Gordon]]\n| Nominated \u2013 [[MTV Movie Award for Best Frightened Performance]]\n|-\n| ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]''\n| Sir Edgar \n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Riverman, The\"| ''The Riverman''\n| [[Ted Bundy]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[American Crime (film)|American Crime]]''\n| Albert Bodine\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2005\n| ''[[Edison (film)|Edison Force]]''\n| District Attorney Jack Reigert\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Neo Ned]]''\n| Dr. Magnuson\n|\n|-\n| ''[[National Lampoon's Pucked]]''\n| Norman\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Cat Returns, The\"| ''[[The Cat Returns]]''\n| Baron Humbert von Gikkingen\n| Voice; English dub\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2006\n| ''[[Factory Girl (2006 film)|Factory Girl]]''\n| Sam Green\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| ''[[Whisper of the Heart (film)|Whisper of the Heart]]''\n| Baron Humbert von Gikkingen\n| Voice; English dub\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2007\n| ''Walk the Talk''\n| Erik\n| Also executive producer\n|-\n| ''[[Georgia Rule]]''\n| Arnold\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| data-sort-value=\"Alphabet Killer, The\"| ''[[The Alphabet Killer]]''\n| Capt. Kenneth Shine\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]''\n| Various characters\n| Voice and motion-capture\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | 2010\n| ''[[Psych 9]]''\n| Dr. Clement\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Flying Lessons (2010 film)|Flying Lessons]]''\n| Steven Jennings\n| \n|-\n| ''[[As Good as Dead (2010 film)|As Good as Dead]]''\n| Ethan Belfrage\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Little Murder]]''\n| Barry Fitzgerald\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| Dr. Lawrence Gordon\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=7 | 2011\n| ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]''\n| Dr. Steven Metzner\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Delhi Safari]]''\n| Bee Commander / Sultan\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[The Adventures of Tintin (film)|The Adventures of Tintin]]''\n| Seaplane Pilot\n| \n|-\n| ''[[New Year's Eve (2011 film)|New Year's Eve]]''\n| Stan's Doctor\n| \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Story of Luke, The\"| ''[[The Story of Luke]]''\n| Uncle Paul\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Camilla Dickinson (film)|Camilla Dickinson]]''\n| Rafferty Dickinson\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Hellgate (2011 film)|Hellgate]]''\n| Jeff Mathews\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2012\n| data-sort-value=\"Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure, The\"| ''[[The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure]]''\n| Bobby Wobbly\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Citizen, The\"| ''[[The Citizen (film)|The Citizen]]''\n| Earl Miller\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 2013\n| ''[[Hansel & Gretel Get Baked]]''\n| Meter Man\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Behaving Badly (film)|Behaving Badly]]''\n| Joseph Stevens\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Justice League: The Flashpoint Paradox]]''\n| [[Aquaman|Orin / Arthur Curry / Aquaman / Emperor Aquaman]]\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Reach Me]]''\n| Kersey\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2015\n| ''[[A Mouse Tale]]'' \n| Sir Thaddeus\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[H8RZ]]'' \n| Principal Donato\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Being Charlie]]''\n| David Mills\n|\n|-\n| ''A Haunting in Cawdor''\n| Lawrence O'Neil\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=6 | 2016\n|Lost and Found\n|John Broman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sugar Mountain (film)|Sugar Mountain]]''\n| Jim Huxley\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Elvis & Nixon]]''\n| {{n/a}}\n| Writer and producer\n|-\n| ''[[Indiscretion (film)|Indiscretion]]''\n| Jake\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Elephant Kingdom'', The\"| ''The Elephant Kingdom''\n| Rock\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[The Queen of Spain]]''\n| Gary Jones\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2017\n| ''[[We Don't Belong Here (film)|We Don't Belong Here]]''\n| Frank Harper\n|\n|-\n| ''Don't Sleep''\n| Dr. Richard Sommers\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2018\n| ''[[Billionaire Boys Club (2018 film)|Billionaire Boys Club]]''\n| [[Andy Warhol]]\n| \n|-\n| ''Ghost Light''\n| Alex Pankhurst\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Black Christmas (2019 film)|Black Christmas]]''\n| Professor Gelson \n| \n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Best Sellers (film)|Best Sellers]]''\n| Halpren Nolan\n| ''Post-production''\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''The Gettysburg Address''\n| Capt. John P. Jones\n| Voice; ''Post-production''\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Shrine (upcoming film)|Shrine]]''\n| Bishop Gyles\n| ''Filming''\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" summary=\"List of Television appearances and roles\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Seinfeld]]''\n| David Lookner\n| Episode: \"[[The Wait Out]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 1998\n|data-sort-value=\"Pentagon Wars, The\"| ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]''\n| Lt. Col. James Burton\n| Television film\n|-\n| ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]''\n| [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]]\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]''\n| Director / [[Hamlet (character)|Hamlet]]\n| Voices; Episodes: \"[[List of Pinky and the Brain episodes#ep50b|Melancholy Brain]]\" and \"[[List of Pinky and the Brain episodes#ep57a|Whatever Happened to Baby Brain]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Hercules (1998 TV series)|Hercules]]''\n| [[Paris of Troy]]\n| Voice; Episode: \"[[List of Hercules: The Animated Series episodes#ep26|Hercules and the Trojan War]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 1999\n|data-sort-value=\"Outer Limits, The\"| ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''\n| Dr. John York\n| Episode: \"[[Ripper (The Outer Limits)|Ripper]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Batman Beyond]]''\n| Paxton Powers\n| Voice; Episode: \"[[List of Batman Beyond episodes#ep13|Ascension]]\"\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Race Against Time''\n| Burke\n| Television film\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2001\n| ''[[Night Visions (TV series)|Night Visions]]''\n| Gerald\n| Episode: \"[[Night Visions (TV series)#ep3b|Quiet Please]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Uprising (2001 film)|Uprising]]''\n| Dr. Fritz Hippler\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2001\u20132002\n|data-sort-value=\"X-Files, The\"| ''[[The X-Files]]''\n| FBI Assistant Director Brad Follmer\n| 6 [[List of The X-Files episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| 2004\n|data-sort-value=\"Riverman, The\"| ''The Riverman''\n| [[Ted Bundy]]\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]''\n| Young Karol Wojtyla\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Haskett's Chance''\n| Mark Haskett / Chris Dalness\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Sidney Truex\n| Episode: \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep175|Dependent]]\"\n|-\n| 2009\u20132014\n| ''[[Psych]]''\n| [[Pierre Despereaux]]\n| 4 [[List of Psych episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Wonder Woman (2011 TV pilot)|Wonder Woman]]''\n| Henry Detmer\n| Unsold pilot \n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2012\n| ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''\n| Scott Roemer\n| Episode: \"[[List of Leverage episodes#ep63|The (Very) Big Bird Job]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Perception (U.S. TV series)|Perception]]''\n| British Intelligence Officer\n| Episode: \"[[List of Perception episodes#ep4|Cipher]]\"\n|-\n| 2013\n|data-sort-value=\"Anna Nicole Story, The\"| ''[[The Anna Nicole Story]]''\n| E. Pierce Marshall\n| Television film\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2014\n| ''[[Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey]]''\n| [[Edmond Halley]] / [[Robert Hooke]]\n| Voices; Episode: \"[[When Knowledge Conquered Fear]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Granite Flats]]''\n| Hugh Ashmead\n| 4 [[Granite Flats#Season Two (2014)|episodes]]\n|-\n| 2014\u20132016\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Himself / [[Dr. Watson]] / Various voices\n| 6 [[List of Family Guy episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015\u20132016\n|data-sort-value=\"Art of More, The\"| ''[[The Art of More]]''\n| Arthur Davenport\n| 20 [[The Art of More#Episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| ''[[Sofia the First]]''\n| Prince Roderick / Basil\n| Voices; Episodes: \"[[List of Sofia the First episodes#ep58|The Secret Library]]\" and \"[[List of Sofia the First episodes#ep73|The Tale of the Noble Knight]]\"\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Life in Pieces]]''\n| Professor Sinclair Wilde\n| 4 [[List of Life in Pieces episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Workaholics]]''\n| Fox\n| Episode: \"[[Workaholics (season 7)#ep82|The Most Dangerless Game]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2018\n| ''[[Youth & Consequences]]''\n| Joel Cutney\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Andr\u00e9 the Giant (film)|Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]''\n| Himself\n| HBO documentary \n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2019\n| ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n| Mayor Larry Kline\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]''\n| Gavin Hawk\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Katy Keene (TV series)|Katy Keene]]''\n|\n|\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Publisher\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Bard's Tale]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gog.com/game/the_bards_tale|title=The Bard's Tale on GOG.com|website=www.gog.com}}</ref>''\n|The Bard\n|Voice\n|[[inXile Entertainment]]\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Epic Mickey 2: The Power of Two]]''\n|Gremlin Gus\n|Voice\n|[[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n|}\n\n== Books ==\n* {{cite book|last=Elwes|first=Cary|last2=Layden|first2=Joe|date=2014|title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNW5BAAAQBAJ|location=New York|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster|Touchstone]]|oclc=878812649|isbn=9781476764023}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|144}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elwes, Cary}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English people of Croatian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:People from Westminster]]\n[[Category:People of Anglo-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n | image            = Cary Elwes September 2015.jpg\n | caption          = Elwes in September 2015\n | birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|10|26}}\n | birth_place      = [[Westminster]], [[London]], England\n | residence        = <!--[[Los Angeles]], [[California (state)|California]], U.S.-->\n | birth_name       = Ivan Simon Cary Elwes\n | occupation       = Actor, writer\n | years_active     = 1979\u2013present\n | alma_mater = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n | parents          = [[Dominick Elwes]]<br/>[[Tessa Kennedy]]\n | relatives        = [[Cassian Elwes]] (brother)<br> [[Damian Elwes]] (brother)\n | spouse           = {{marriage|Lisa Marie Kurbikoff|2000}} \n | children         = 1}}\n\n'''Ivan Simon Cary Elwes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|l|w|\u026a|s}}; born 26 October 1962)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2008/10/26/The_almanac/UPI-34121225006200|title=The Almanac|publisher=UPI|date=26 October 2008|accessdate=29 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=World Almanac|work=[[Kent County Daily Times]]|date=26 October 2010|quote=Today's Birthdays: Cary Elwes}}</ref> is an English actor and writer.<ref name=\"thewrap.com\">{{cite news|last1=Reilly|first1=Travis|title=Colin Hanks, Johnny Knoxville, Alex Pettyfer Added to 'Elvis & Nixon'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/colin-hanks-johnny-knoxville-alex-pettyfer-added-to-elvis-nixon/|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=16 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2014-11-02/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 November 2014|language=en}}</ref> He is best known for his leading film roles as Westley in ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'' (1987), [[Robin Hood]] in ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]'' (1993), and [[Dr. Lawrence Gordon]] in the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' film series]]. He is also known for leading roles in films like ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' (1991), and ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' (1994), as well as supporting roles in films including ''[[Days of Thunder]]'' (1990), ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'' (1996), ''[[Kiss the Girls (1997 film)|Kiss the Girls]]'' (1997), ''[[Liar Liar]]'' (1997), Michael Collins in ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (1998), ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]'' (1999), ''[[Shadow of the Vampire]]'' (2000), ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' (2001), ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]'' (2004), ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'' (2009), and ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=caryelwes.htm|title=Cary Elwes Movie Box Office Results|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref> He has had recurring roles in television series including ''[[The X-Files]]'', ''[[Psych]]'', and ''[[Stranger Things (season 3)|Stranger Things]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/02/arts/television/stranger-things-netflix-cary-elwes.html|title='Stranger Things': Cary Elwes Lives It Up As a Shady Mayor|first=Brian|last=Tallerico|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He joined the third season of ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'' as Gavin Hawk, a famed [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] actor.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/marvelous-mrs-maisel-season-3-cary-elwes-stephanie-hsu-1203229363/|first=Joe|last=Otterson| title='Marvelous Mrs. Maisel' Season 3 Adds Cary Elwes, Stephanie Hsu (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=30 May 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nIvan Simon Cary Elwes was born on 26 October 1962 in [[Westminster|Westminster, London]], the youngest of three sons of portrait painter [[Dominic Elwes]]<ref name=\"People1995\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105004,00.html |title=A Hero to the Hilt |last=Cerio |first=Gregory |volume=43 |work=[[People (American magazine)|People]] |date=6 February 1995 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110330190839/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20105004,00.html |archivedate=30 March 2011 |url-status=live |issue=5 |df=dmy }}</ref> and interior designer and socialite [[Tessa Kennedy]]. He is the brother of artist [[Damian Elwes]]<ref name=\"Chicago1990\"/> and film producer [[Cassian Elwes]]. His stepfather, [[Elliott Kastner]], was an American film producer.<ref name=\"People1995\"/> His paternal grandfather was painter [[Simon Elwes]],<ref name=\"Chicago1990\">{{cite news|first=Jae-Ha|last=Kim|title=British actor takes turn as American in 'Glory'|page=25|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=12 January 1990}}</ref> whose own father was the diplomat and tenor [[Gervase Elwes]] (1866\u20131921).<ref>{{cite book|title=Loose Canon: A Portrait of Brian Brindley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=At3vy0eh2LUC&pg=PA134&dq=Gervase+Elwes+Simon#v=onepage&q=Gervase%20Elwes%20Simon&f=false|last=Thompson|first=Damian|authorlink=Damian Thompson|page=134|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]]|isbn=0-8264-7418-7|date=22 June 2004}}</ref> His other great-grandfathers include the diplomat [[Rennell Rodd, 1st Baron Rennell]] and industrialist [[Ivan Rikard Ivanovi\u0107]]. Elwes has  [[English people|English]], [[Irish people|Irish]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], [[History of the Jews in Croatia|Croatian Jewish]], and [[Serbs|Serbian]] ancestry,<ref>90265 Malibu Life & Style Magazine Issue No. 2; Fall 2013</ref> the latter two from his maternal grandmother, Da\u0161ka McLean, whose second husband, [[Neil McLean (politician)|Billy McLean]], was an operative for [[Special Operations Executive]] during [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patrickleighfermor.org/2010/07/01/one-mans-great-game-lieutenant-colonel-%E2%80%9Cbilly%E2%80%9D-mclean/|title=One Man\u2019s Great Game: Lieutenant Colonel \"Billy\" McLean - Patrick Leigh Fermor|work=Patrick Leigh Fermor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://soetrails.wordpress.com/tag/billy-mclean/page/2/|title=Billy McLean - S.O.E. Trails|first=Billy|last=McLean|date=4 March 2013|publisher=S.O.E. Trails}}</ref>\n\nOne of Elwes's relatives is [[John Elwes (politician)|John Elwes]], who was believed to be the inspiration for [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] in ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'' (1843), having been referenced by [[Charles Dickens]] himself in chapter six of his last completed novel, ''[[Our Mutual Friend]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.literaturepage.com/read/dickens-our-mutual-friend-577.html||first=Michael| last=Moncur|publisher=The Literature Page|title=Charles Dickens: Our Mutual Friend}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/only-in-britain/man-who-inspired-ebenezer-scrooge/|title=John Elwes: scrimper who inspired Ebenezer Scrooge|first=Norman|last=Miller|date=20 September 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> Elwes himself played five roles in the [[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|2009 film adaptation]] of ''A Christmas Carol''. Through his maternal grandfather, Elwes is also related to [[Alexander Kennedy|Sir Alexander William \"Blackie\" Kennedy]], one of the first photographers to document the archaeological site of [[Petra]] following the collapse of the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.genealogy.com/forum/surnames/topics/kennedy/658/|title=Sir Alexander Blackie William| publisher= Genealogy.com}}</ref>\n\nElwes was brought up as a [[Roman Catholic]] and was an [[altar boy]] at [[Westminster Cathedral]], although he did not attend [[denominational]] schools as most of the men on his father's side of the family had, including his father.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guthrie |first=Marisa |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2005/12/04/2005-12-04_the_spirit_moved_him.html |title=The spirit moved him |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |quote=Elwes, who grew up a Catholic... |date=4 December 2005 |accessdate=13 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61zzNYuVF?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2005-12-04/entertainment/18305424_1_vatican-residence-pope-john-paul-ii-papal |archivedate=27 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> His paternal relatives include such [[clerics]] as [[Dudley Charles Cary-Elwes]] (1868\u20131932), the [[Roman Catholic]] [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Northampton|Bishop of Northampton]], Abbott [[Columba Cary-Elwes]] ([[Ampleforth Abbey]], [[Saint Louis Abbey]]), and Father Luke Cary-Elwes ([[Fort Augustus Abbey]]). He discussed this in an interview while he was filming the 2005 [[CBS]] television film ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]'', in which he played the young priest [[Karol Wojty\u0142a]].\n\nElwes's parents divorced when he was four years old. In 1975, when Elwes was 13, his father died by suicide. He was educated at [[Harrow School]],<ref name=\"Chicago1990\"/> and the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]].<ref name=\"StraitsTimes\">{{cite journal|title=Dr Gordon is back in Saw \u2013 Cary Elwes's character from the first Saw film is back by popular demand|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=5 January 2011}}</ref> In 1981, he moved to the United States to study acting at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in [[Bronxville, New York]].<ref name=\"Chronicle1993\">{{cite journal|title=The 'Robin' Who Has Sherwood Forest Chuckling|last=Tam Jr|first=Henry|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|page=C6|date=13 August 1993}}</ref> While living there, Elwes studied acting at both the [[Actors Studio]]<ref name=\"Chronicle1993\"/> and the [[Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute]] under the tutelage of [[Al Pacino]]'s mentor, Charlie Laughton (not to be confused with English actor [[Charles Laughton]]).<ref name=\"StraitsTimes\"/> As a teenager, he also worked as a production assistant on the films ''[[Absolution (1978 film)|Absolution]]'', ''[[Octopussy]]'', and ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'', where he was assigned to [[Marlon Brando]]. When Elwes introduced himself to the famous actor, Brando insisted on calling him \"Rocky\" after [[Rocky Marciano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q2yqE_QYanU|title=Mark & Brian w/Cary Elwes on Marlon Brando|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=8 May 2008|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Film ===\nElwes made his acting [[:wikt:debut|debut]] in 1984 with [[Marek Kanievska]]'s film ''[[Another Country (film)|Another Country]]'', which was loosely based on the English [[boarding school]] exploits of British spies, [[Guy Burgess|Burgess]], [[Kim Philby|Philby]] and [[Donald Maclean (spy)|MacLean]]. He played James Harcourt, a gay student.<ref name=\"Chicago1990\"/> He went on to play [[Guilford Dudley]] in the British historical drama film ''[[Lady Jane (1986 film)|Lady Jane]]'', opposite [[Helena Bonham Carter]]. He was then cast as a stable-boy-turned-swashbuckler Westley in [[Rob Reiner]]'s fantasy-comedy ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'', which was based on the [[The Princess Bride (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[William Goldman]]. It was a modest box office success,<ref name=\"Bride\">{{cite journal|title='The Princess Bride' Turns 20|journal=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|page=6J|last=Gray Streeter|first=Leslie|date=9 December 2007|quote=[w]as a modest hit. But it became a raging cult classic after being released on video and shown on cable.}}</ref> but received critical acclaim, earning a score of 97% on the review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/princess_bride|title=The Princess Bride (1987)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> Since being released on home video and television, the film has become a [[cult film|cult classic]].<ref name=\"Bride\"/>\n\n{{Quote|Initially the studio didn't know how to market it. Was it an adventure? A fantasy? A comedy? A romance? A kid's movie? In the end they sold it as a kid's movie and it largely had to rely on word of mouth ... people tell me they still have their [[VHS]] copy that has been passed down from one generation to the next.|Interview from the film's DVD release in 2001<ref>{{cite news |title='Bride' basks in glow of video|work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |last=Westbrook|first=Bruce|date=6 September 2001}}</ref>}}\n\nElwes continued to work steadily, varying between dramatic roles, such as in the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]'' (1989), and comedic roles, as in ''[[Hot Shots!]]'' (1991). In 1993, he starred as [[Robin Hood]] in [[Mel Brooks]]'s comedy, ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]''. Elwes then appeared in supporting roles in such films as [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s adaptation of ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]'', ''[[The Crush (1993 film)|The Crush]]'', ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' (1994), ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]'', ''[[Liar Liar]]'', and ''[[Kiss the Girls (1997 film)|Kiss the Girls]]''. In 1999, he portrayed famed theatre and film producer [[John Houseman]] for [[Tim Robbins]] in his ensemble film based on [[Orson Welles]]'s musical, ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]''. Following that, he travelled to [[Luxembourg]] to work with [[John Malkovich]] and [[Willem Dafoe]] in ''[[Shadow of the Vampire]]''. In 2001, he co-starred in [[Peter Bogdanovich]]'s ensemble film ''[[The Cat's Meow]]'' portraying movie mogul [[Thomas H. Ince|Thomas Ince]], who died mysteriously while vacationing with [[William Randolph Hearst]] on his [[yacht]].\n\nIn 2004, Elwes starred in the [[Horror film|horror]]\u2013[[Thriller film|thriller]] ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' which, at a budget of a little over $1&nbsp;million, grossed over $100&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"SawBOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw.htm|title=Saw (2004) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref> The same year he appeared in ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]'', this time as the villain, not the hero. He made an uncredited appearance as [[Samuel Adams Green|Sam Green]], the man who introduced [[Andy Warhol]] to [[Edie Sedgwick]], in the 2006 film ''[[Factory Girl (2006 film)|Factory Girl]]''. In 2007, he appeared in [[Garry Marshall]]'s ''[[Georgia Rule]]'' opposite [[Jane Fonda]].\n\nIn 2010, he returned to the ''Saw'' franchise in ''[[Saw 3D]]'' (2010), the seventh film in the series, as Dr. [[Lawrence Gordon (character)|Lawrence Gordon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19954/ |title=Cary Elwes Confirmed for 'Saw 3D', Full Synopsis and Cast |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |date=25 April 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2010 |archivedate=26 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426192519/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/19954 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2011, he was selected by [[Ivan Reitman]] to star alongside [[Natalie Portman]] in ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]''. That same year, Elwes and [[Garry Marshall]] teamed up again in the ensemble romantic comedy ''New Year's Eve'' opposite [[Robert de Niro]] and [[Halle Berry]].\n\nIn 2012, Elwes starred in the independent drama ''[[The Citizen (film)|The Citizen]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118039848 |title=4 thesps apply for 'The Citizen' |last=Sneider |first=Jeff |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820004206/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118039848 |archivedate=20 August 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> and the following year Elwes joined [[Selena Gomez]] for the comedy ensemble, ''[[Behaving Badly (film)|Behaving Badly]]'' directed by Tim Garrick. In 2014, he starred in [[John Herzfeld]]'s ensemble comedy ''[[Reach Me]]''. In 2015, he completed four movies: the ensemble drama ''[[Sugar Mountain (film)|Sugar Mountain]]'' directed by Richard Gray; and the dramas ''[[H8RZ]]'', directed by Derrick Borte, ''[[We Don't Belong Here (film)|We Don't Belong Here]]'', opposite [[Anton Yelchin]] and [[Catherine Keener]] directed by Peer Pedersen, and ''[[Being Charlie]]'' which reunited Elwes with director [[Rob Reiner]] after 28 years and premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]].\n\nIn January 2016, Elwes portrayed [[Andy Warhol]] opposite [[Kevin Spacey]] in ''[[Billionaire Boys Club (2016 film)|The Billionaire Boys Club]]'' directed by [[James Cox (director)|James Cox]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/these-upcoming-kevin-spacey-movies-shows-may-be-in-trouble-now.html/?a=viewall|title=These Upcoming Kevin Spacey Projects May Be in Trouble Now|date=1 December 2017|work=The Cheat Sheet|access-date=10 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\nElwes made his first television appearance in 1996 as David Lookner on ''[[Seinfeld]]''. Two years later he played astronaut [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]] in the [[Golden Globe Award]]-winning [[HBO]] [[miniseries]] ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth To the Moon]]''. The following year Elwes was nominated for a [[Golden Satellite Award]] for Best Performance by an Actor in a Mini-Series or Motion Picture Made for Television for his portrayal of Colonel [[James G. Burton|James Burton]] in ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]'' directed by [[Richard Benjamin]]. In 1999, he guest starred as Dr. John York in an episode of the television series ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''. Shortly afterward he received another [[Golden Satellite Award]] nomination for his work on the ensemble NBC Television movie ''[[Uprising (2001 film)|Uprising]]'' opposite [[Jon Voight]] directed by [[Jon Avnet]]. Elwes had a recurring role in the final season (from 2001 to 2002) of [[Chris Carter (screenwriter)|Chris Carter]]'s hit series ''[[The X-Files]]'' as [[FBI Assistant Director]] [[Brad Follmer]].\n\nIn 2004, he portrayed serial killer [[Ted Bundy]] in the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E Network]] film ''The Riverman'', which became one of the highest rated original movies in the network's history and garnered a prestigious [[Banff World Media Festival|BANFF Rockie Award]] nomination. The following year, Elwes played the young [[Pope John Paul II|Karol Wojty\u0142a]] in the [[CBS]] television film ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]'', his second time working with [[Jon Voight]]. The TV film was highly successful not only in North America but also in Europe, where it broke box office records in the late Pope's native [[Poland]] and became the first film ever to break $1&nbsp;million (GBP 739,075.00 current) in three days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pope Picture Breaks Box Office Records|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/pope%20picture%20breaks%20box%20office%20records%20in%20poland_09_03_2006|publisher=contactmusic.com|date=3 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he made a guest appearance on the ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' episode \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep14|Dependent]]\" as a [[Mafia]] lawyer. In 2009, he played the role of [[Pierre Despereaux]], an international art thief, in the fourth-season premiere of ''[[Psych]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35164/first-two-teaser-clips-psych-9 |title=First Two Teaser Clips Psych: 9 |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |date=2 January 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102224255/http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35164/first-two-teaser-clips-psych-9 |archivedate=2 November 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2010, he returned to ''[[Psych]]'', reprising his role in the second half of the [[Psych (season 5)|fifth season]], again in the show's [[Psych (season 6)|sixth season]], and again in the show's [[Psych (season 8)|eighth season]] premiere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/07/psych-spoiler-video-season-6-james-roday-dule-hill |title=Psych First Look: The Season 6 Scene Everyone Will Be Talking About! Plus, Musical Update! |last=Slezak |first=Michael |work=TVLine |date=21 July 2011 |accessdate=27 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923042810/http://www.tvline.com/2011/07/psych-spoiler-video-season-6-james-roday-dule-hill/ |archivedate=23 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2014 Elwes played Hugh Ashmeade, Director of the [[CIA]], in the second season of the BYUtv series ''[[Granite Flats]]''.\n\nIn May 2015, Elwes was cast as a series regular in [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]]'s first streaming network series drama, ''[[The Art of More]]'', which explores the cutthroat world of premium auction houses. He played Arthur Davenport, a shrewd and eccentric world-class collector of illegal art and antiquities. The series debuted on 19 November and was picked up for a second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/cary-elwes-cast-the-art-of-more-drama-series-crackle-1201420939/|title=Cary Elwes Joins \u2018The Art Of More\u2019 Drama Series On Crackle|first=Denise|last=Petski|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 Elwes was cast as Larry Kline, Mayor of Hawkins, for the third season of the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Stranger Things]]'', which premiered in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/stranger-things-s3-casting-announcement|title=Stranger Things S3 Casting Announcement|work=[[Netflix]]|language=en|access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref> In May 2019, it was announced that he would be joining the third season of the [[Amazon Studios|Amazon]] series ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'' as Gavin Hawk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/05/cary-elwes-marvelous-mrs-maisel-season-3|title=Cary Elwes and His Smoldering Eyes Are Joining Marvelous Mrs. Maisel Season 3|first=Kevin|last=Fitzpatrick|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Voice-over work ===\nElwes's [[voice-over]] work includes the narrator in [[James Patterson]]'s [[audiobook]] ''[[The Jester (novel)|The Jester]]'',<ref>{{cite book|title=The Jester|last=Paterson|first=James|authorlink=James Patterson|last2=Gross|first2=Andrew|authorlink2=Andrew Gross|isbn=1-58621-535-3|publisher=[[Hachette Audio]]| edition=Abridged|date=1 March 2003}}</ref> as well as characters in film and [[television animation]]s such as ''[[Quest for Camelot]]'', ''[[Pinky and The Brain]]'', ''[[Batman Beyond]]'', and the English versions of the [[Studio Ghibli]] films, ''[[Porco Rosso]]'', ''[[Whisper of the Heart (film)|Whisper of the Heart]]'' and ''[[The Cat Returns]]''. For the 2004 video game ''[[The Bard's Tale (2004)|The Bard's Tale]]'', he served as screenwriter, improviser, and voice actor of the main character The Bard. In 2009, Elwes reunited with [[Jason Alexander]] for the [[Indian film]], ''[[Delhi Safari]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2011/05/30/15833/index.html |title=Delhi Safari to feature voice over by Vanessa Williams and Jason Alexander |work=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |date=30 May 2011 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904200314/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2011/05/30/15833/index.html |archivedate=4 September 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The following year Elwes portrayed the part of Gremlin Gus in Disney's video game, ''[[Epic Mickey 2: The Power of Two]]''. In 2014, he appeared in ''[[Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey]]'' as the voice of scientists [[Edmond Halley]] and [[Robert Hooke]].\n\n=== Motion capture work ===\nIn 2009 Elwes joined the cast of [[Robert Zemeckis]]'s [[motion capture]] adaptation of [[Charles Dickens]]' ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'' portraying five roles. That same year he was chosen by [[Steven Spielberg]] to appear in his [[motion capture]] adaptation of Belgian artist [[Herg\u00e9]]'s popular comic strip ''[[The Adventures of Tintin: The Secret of the Unicorn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a347079/the-adventures-of-tintin-premieres-in-london-pictures.html#~p5ZywC1hHstyq3|title='The Adventures of Tintin' premieres in London \u2013 Pictures|work=Digital Spy}}</ref>\n\n=== Theatre ===\nIn 2003 Elwes portrayed [[Kerry Max Cook]] in the [[off-Broadway]] play ''[[The Exonerated (play)|The Exonerated]]'' in New York, directed by [[Bob Balaban]] (18\u201323 March 2003).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/78481-Cary-Elwes-and-Brooke-Shields-Join-Off-Broadways-Exonerated-March-18-23 |title=Cary Elwes and Brooke Shields Join Off-Broadway's ''Exonerated'', 18\u201323 March |last=Hernandez |first=Ernio |work=Playbill.com |date=18 March 2003 |accessdate=27 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629082056/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/78481-Cary-Elwes-and-Brooke-Shields-Join-Off-Broadways-Exonerated-March-18-23 |archivedate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\nIn October 2014 Touchstone ([[Simon & Schuster]]) published Elwes's memoir of the making of ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]'', entitled ''As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride'', which Elwes co-wrote with Joe Layden. The book featured never-before-told stories, exclusive behind-the-scenes photographs, and interviews with co-stars [[Robin Wright]], [[Wallace Shawn]], [[Billy Crystal]], [[Christopher Guest]], [[Fred Savage]] and [[Mandy Patinkin]], as well as author and screenwriter [[William Goldman]], producer [[Norman Lear]], and director [[Rob Reiner]]. The book debuted on ''[[The New York Times Best Seller list]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2014-11-02/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 November 2014|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.geekwithcurves.com/2014/06/cary-elwes-wrote-book-about-princess.html|title=Cary Elwes wrote book about the making of the film, ''The Princess Bride''|publisher= geekwithcurves.com|date=June 2014|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Other projects ===\nIn 2014, Elwes co-wrote the screenplay for a film entitled ''[[Elvis & Nixon]]'', about the pair's famous meeting at the [[White House]] in 1970.<ref name=\"thewrap.com\"/> The film, which starred [[Michael Shannon]] and [[Kevin Spacey]], was bought by [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] as their first theatrical feature and was released on 22 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/amazon-elvis-nixon-kevin-spacey-1201500537/|date=23 June 2015|title=\u2018Elvis & Nixon\u2019 Starring Kevin Spacey Sold to Amazon|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n== Lawsuit ==\nIn August 2005, Elwes filed a lawsuit against [[Evolution Entertainment]], his management firm and producer of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''. Elwes said he was promised a minimum of one percent of the producers' net profits of the film and did not receive the full amount.<ref name=\"Cary\">{{cite news|title=Not everyone happy with their cut from Saw |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/film/not-everyone-happy-with-their-cut-from-saw/2005/08/20/1124435169494.html |last=Mitchell |first=Peter |agency=[[Association of American Publishers|AAP]] |work=[[The Age]] |date=20 August 2005 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107064640/http://www.theage.com.au/news/film/not-everyone-happy-with-their-cut-from-saw/2005/08/20/1124435169494.html |archivedate=7 November 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> The case was [[legal settlement|settled out of court]]. In 2010, he reprised his role in ''[[Saw 3D]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fangoria.com/index.php?id=641:saw-vii-synopsis-and-cast-revealedincluding-cary-elwes&option=com_content&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=167 |title=\"Saw VII\" Synopsis and Cast Revealed \u2013 Including Cary Elwes! |last=Gingold |first=Michael |work=[[Fangoria]] |date=25 April 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614095114/http://www.fangoria.com/index.php?id=641:saw-vii-synopsis-and-cast-revealedincluding-cary-elwes&option=com_content&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=167 |archivedate=14 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nElwes met photographer Lisa Marie Kurbikoff in 1991 at a [[Cook-off#Chili cook-off|chili cook-off]] in [[Malibu, California]], and they became engaged in 1997.<ref name=\"Marriage\">{{cite journal|title=Celebrities \u2013 DeGeneres 'Bedding' Talk-Show Guests|work=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|date=3 May 2007|page=D2|quote=Elwes and Lisa Marie (''n\u00e9e'' Kurbikoff) met in 1991 at a Malibu chili cook-off. They were engaged in 1997 and tied the knot three years later.}}</ref> They married in 2000 and have one daughter together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20037158,00.html |title=Cary Elwes, Wife Welcome a Girl |last=Silverman |first=Stephen M. |last2=Jordan |first2=Julie |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=27 April 2007 |accessdate=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107065256/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20037158,00.html |archivedate=7 November 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" summary=\"List of films and roles\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Yesterday's Hero]]''\n| Disco Dancer\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2| 1984\n| ''[[Another Country (film)|Another Country]]''\n| James Harcourt\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Oxford Blues]]''\n| Lionel\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| data-sort-value=\"Bride, The\"| ''[[The Bride (1985 film)|The Bride]]''\n| Capt. Josef Schoden\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Lady Jane (1986 film)|Lady Jane]]''\n| [[Guilford Dudley]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1987\n| ''[[Maschenka (1987 film)|Maschenka]]''\n| Lev Glebovich Ganin\n| \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Princess Bride, The\"| ''[[The Princess Bride (film)|The Princess Bride]]''\n| Westley / [[Dread Pirate Roberts]]\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Never on Tuesday]]''\n| Tow Truck Driver\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Glory (1989 film)|Glory]]''\n| Maj. Cabot Forbes\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Days of Thunder]]''\n| Russ Wheeler\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Hot Shots!]]''\n| Lt. Kent Gregory\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1992\n| ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]''\n| Lord [[Arthur Holmwood]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Leather Jackets (film)|Leather Jackets]]''\n| Dobbs\n| Also associate producer\n|-\n| ''[[Porco Rosso]]''\n| Donald Curtis (voice)\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1993\n| ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights]]''\n| [[Robin Hood]]\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Crush, The\"| ''[[The Crush (1993 film)|The Crush]]''\n| Nick Eliot\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1994\n| data-sort-value=\"Jungle Book, The\"| ''[[The Jungle Book (1994 film)|The Jungle Book]]''\n| Capt. William Boone\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Chase, The\"| ''[[The Chase (1994 film)|The Chase]]''\n| Steve Horsegroovy\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Twister (1996 film)|Twister]]''\n| Dr. Jonas Miller\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 1997\n| ''[[Kiss the Girls (1997 film)|Kiss the Girls]]''\n| Det. Nick Ruskin\n| Nominated \u2013 [[Blockbuster Entertainment Awards]] Best Supporting ActoDet\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Informant, The\"| ''[[The Informant (1997 film)|The Informant]]''\n| Lt. David Ferris\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Liar Liar]]''\n| Jerry\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Quest for Camelot]]''\n| Garrett\n| Voice\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]''\n| Col. James G. Burton\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Cradle Will Rock]]''\n| [[John Houseman]]\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Shadow of the Vampire]]''\n| [[Fritz Arno Wagner|Fritz Arno \"Fritzy\" Wagner]]\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| data-sort-value=\"Cat's Meow, The\"| ''[[The Cat's Meow]]''\n| [[Thomas H. Ince]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2002\n| ''[[Wish You Were Dead]]''\n| Mac \"Macbeth\" Wilson\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Comic Book Villains]]''\n| Carter\n| Also co-producer\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Porco Rosso]]''\n| Donald Curtis\n| Voice; English dub\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2004\n| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| Dr. [[Lawrence Gordon (character)|Lawrence Gordon]]\n| Nominated \u2013 [[MTV Movie Award for Best Frightened Performance]]\n|-\n| ''[[Ella Enchanted (film)|Ella Enchanted]]''\n| Sir Edgar \n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Riverman, The\"| ''The Riverman''\n| [[Ted Bundy]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[American Crime (film)|American Crime]]''\n| Albert Bodine\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2005\n| ''[[Edison (film)|Edison Force]]''\n| District Attorney Jack Reigert\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Neo Ned]]''\n| Dr. Magnuson\n|\n|-\n| ''[[National Lampoon's Pucked]]''\n| Norman\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Cat Returns, The\"| ''[[The Cat Returns]]''\n| Baron Humbert von Gikkingen\n| Voice; English dub\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2006\n| ''[[Factory Girl (2006 film)|Factory Girl]]''\n| Sam Green\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| ''[[Whisper of the Heart (film)|Whisper of the Heart]]''\n| Baron Humbert von Gikkingen\n| Voice; English dub\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2007\n| ''Walk the Talk''\n| Erik\n| Also executive producer\n|-\n| ''[[Georgia Rule]]''\n| Arnold\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| data-sort-value=\"Alphabet Killer, The\"| ''[[The Alphabet Killer]]''\n| Capt. Kenneth Shine\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[A Christmas Carol (2009 film)|A Christmas Carol]]''\n| Various characters\n| Voice and motion-capture\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | 2010\n| ''[[Psych 9]]''\n| Dr. Clement\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Flying Lessons (2010 film)|Flying Lessons]]''\n| Steven Jennings\n| \n|-\n| ''[[As Good as Dead (2010 film)|As Good as Dead]]''\n| Ethan Belfrage\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Little Murder]]''\n| Barry Fitzgerald\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| Dr. Lawrence Gordon\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=7 | 2011\n| ''[[No Strings Attached (2011 film)|No Strings Attached]]''\n| Dr. Steven Metzner\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Delhi Safari]]''\n| Bee Commander / Sultan\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[The Adventures of Tintin (film)|The Adventures of Tintin]]''\n| Seaplane Pilot\n| \n|-\n| ''[[New Year's Eve (2011 film)|New Year's Eve]]''\n| Stan's Doctor\n| \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Story of Luke, The\"| ''[[The Story of Luke]]''\n| Uncle Paul\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Camilla Dickinson (film)|Camilla Dickinson]]''\n| Rafferty Dickinson\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Hellgate (2011 film)|Hellgate]]''\n| Jeff Mathews\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2012\n| data-sort-value=\"Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure, The\"| ''[[The Oogieloves in the Big Balloon Adventure]]''\n| Bobby Wobbly\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Citizen, The\"| ''[[The Citizen (film)|The Citizen]]''\n| Earl Miller\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=3 | 2013\n| ''[[Hansel & Gretel Get Baked]]''\n| Meter Man\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Behaving Badly (film)|Behaving Badly]]''\n| Joseph Stevens\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Justice League: The Flashpoint Paradox]]''\n| [[Aquaman|Orin / Arthur Curry / Aquaman / Emperor Aquaman]]\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Reach Me]]''\n| Kersey\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | 2015\n| ''[[A Mouse Tale]]'' \n| Sir Thaddeus\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[H8RZ]]'' \n| Principal Donato\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Being Charlie]]''\n| David Mills\n|\n|-\n| ''A Haunting in Cawdor''\n| Lawrence O'Neil\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=6 | 2016\n|Lost and Found\n|John Broman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sugar Mountain (film)|Sugar Mountain]]''\n| Jim Huxley\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Elvis & Nixon]]''\n| {{n/a}}\n| Writer and producer\n|-\n| ''[[Indiscretion (film)|Indiscretion]]''\n| Jake\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Elephant Kingdom'', The\"| ''The Elephant Kingdom''\n| Rock\n| Voice\n|-\n| ''[[The Queen of Spain]]''\n| Gary Jones\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2017\n| ''[[We Don't Belong Here (film)|We Don't Belong Here]]''\n| Frank Harper\n|\n|-\n| ''Don't Sleep''\n| Dr. Richard Sommers\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 2018\n| ''[[Billionaire Boys Club (2018 film)|Billionaire Boys Club]]''\n| [[Andy Warhol]]\n| \n|-\n| ''Ghost Light''\n| Alex Pankhurst\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Black Christmas (2019 film)|Black Christmas]]''\n| Professor Gelson \n| \n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Best Sellers (film)|Best Sellers]]''\n| Halpren Nolan\n| ''Post-production''\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''The Gettysburg Address''\n| Capt. John P. Jones\n| Voice; ''Post-production''\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Shrine (upcoming film)|Shrine]]''\n| Bishop Gyles\n| ''Filming''\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" summary=\"List of Television appearances and roles\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Seinfeld]]''\n| David Lookner\n| Episode: \"[[The Wait Out]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 1998\n|data-sort-value=\"Pentagon Wars, The\"| ''[[The Pentagon Wars]]''\n| Lt. Col. James Burton\n| Television film\n|-\n| ''[[From the Earth 