an=2| 2012\n| ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''\n| Scott Roemer\n| Episode: \"[[List of Leverage episodes#ep63|The (Very) Big Bird Job]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Perception (U.S. TV series)|Perception]]''\n| British Intelligence Officer\n| Episode: \"[[List of Perception episodes#ep4|Cipher]]\"\n|-\n| 2013\n|data-sort-value=\"Anna Nicole Story, The\"| ''[[The Anna Nicole Story]]''\n| E. Pierce Marshall\n| Television film\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2014\n| ''[[Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey]]''\n| [[Edmond Halley]] / [[Robert Hooke]]\n| Voices; Episode: \"[[When Knowledge Conquered Fear]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Granite Flats]]''\n| Hugh Ashmead\n| 4 [[Granite Flats#Season Two (2014)|episodes]]\n|-\n| 2014\u20132016\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Himself / [[Dr. Watson]] / Various voices\n| 6 [[List of Family Guy episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015\u20132016\n|data-sort-value=\"Art of More, The\"| ''[[The Art of More]]''\n| Arthur Davenport\n| 20 [[The Art of More#Episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| ''[[Sofia the First]]''\n| Prince Roderick / Basil\n| Voices; Episodes: \"[[List of Sofia the First episodes#ep58|The Secret Library]]\" and \"[[List of Sofia the First episodes#ep73|The Tale of the Noble Knight]]\"\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Life in Pieces]]''\n| Professor Sinclair Wilde\n| 4 [[List of Life in Pieces episodes|episodes]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Workaholics]]''\n| Fox\n| Episode: \"[[Workaholics (season 7)#ep82|The Most Dangerless Game]]\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2018\n| ''[[Youth & Consequences]]''\n| Joel Cutney\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Andr\u00e9 the Giant (film)|Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]''\n| Himself\n| HBO documentary \n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2019\n| ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n| Mayor Larry Kline\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]''\n| Gavin Hawk\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Katy Keene (TV series)|Katy Keene]]''\n|\n|\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Publisher\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Bard's Tale]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gog.com/game/the_bards_tale|title=The Bard's Tale on GOG.com|website=www.gog.com}}</ref>''\n|The Bard\n|Voice\n|[[inXile Entertainment]]\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Epic Mickey 2: The Power of Two]]''\n|Gremlin Gus\n|Voice\n|[[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n|}\n\n== Books ==\n* {{cite book|last=Elwes|first=Cary|last2=Layden|first2=Joe|date=2014|title=As You Wish: Inconceivable Tales from the Making of The Princess Bride|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNW5BAAAQBAJ|location=New York|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster|Touchstone]]|oclc=878812649|isbn=9781476764023}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|144}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elwes, Cary}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English people of Croatian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:People from Westminster]]\n[[Category:People of Anglo-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:4028:ae00:fd1b:c656:adff:3e3a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cary_Elwes"}
{"title_page": "Beata Rank", "text_new": "'''Beata Rank-Minzer''', born '''Beata Minzer''' or '''Munzer''', known to friends by the nickname '''Tola''' (1886 - 1967) was a Polish-American psychoanalyst.<ref name=IDP>Helene Rank-Veltfort, [https://www.encyclopedia.com/psychology/dictionaries-thesauruses-pictures-and-press-releases/rank-minzer-munzer-beata-1886-1961 Rank-Minzer (Munzer), Beata (1886-1961)], ''International Dictionary of Psychoanalysis''. Online at encyclopedia.com. Accessed 28 March 2020.</ref><ref>[[Paul Roazen]], 'Tola Rank', ''Revue internationale d'histoire de la psychanalyse'', 1990.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBeata Minzer was born on February 16, 1886 in [[Neusandetz]] near [[Krakow]], Poland, then part of the [[Austrian-Hungarian Empire]].<ref name=IDP/> Her aunt instroduced her to [[Otto Rank]], who was stationed in Krakow editing the ''Krakauer Zeitung'' from 1916-18. They married in a Jewish wedding ceremony on November 7, 1918, days before the end of [[World War I]]. The couple moved to [[Vienna]] soon afterwards, where Otto took her to present to [[Sigmund Freud]] as a sort of 'court presentation'.<ref name=\"GeissmannGeissmann2005\">{{cite book|author1=Pierre Geissmann|author2=Claudine Geissmann|title=A History of Child Psychoanalysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqyIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA134|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-83002-2|pages=134\u20137}}</ref> Their only child, Helene, was born in August 1919. \n\nThough Freud's initial impression of Beata Rank had been unfavourable - \"a little Polish-Jewish wife whom no-one finds congenial and who betrays no higher interests\" \u2013 he soon revised his opinion.<ref name=\"Gay1998\">{{cite book|last=Gay|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Gay|title=Freud: A Life for Our Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mZ5eX44E9lYC&pg=PA471|year=1998|publisher=W. W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-07234-1|pages=471\u20132}}</ref>\nShe became [[Freud]]'s hostess for social events, entertaining visitors like [[Lou Andreas-Salom\u00e9]].<ref name=\"Lieberman2010\">{{cite book|author=E. James Lieberman|title=Acts of Will: The Life and Work of Otto Rank|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HWB38ycJxd0C&pg=PA155|year=2010|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4391-1915-0|page=155}}</ref> She attended lectures and seminars on psychoanalysis. Like [[Anna Freud]] \u2013 who felt some rivalry towards her \u2013\u00a0she took dictation from Freud in the publication of ''Imago''.<ref name=\"GeissmannGeissmann2005\"/> In 1923 she translated [[Freud]]'s ''On Dreams'' \u2013 an abridged version of ''[[The Interpretation of Dreams]]'' \u2013\u00a0into Polish. A 1923 paper on the role of women in the development of human society, which integrated Freud's theory of [[Oedipal conflict]] with [[Bachofen]]'s' [[mother-right]] theory,<ref>J. C. F., [https://www.pep-web.org/document.php?id=ijp.007.0089a Applied Psycho-Analysis: Beata Rank. Zur Rolle der Frau in der Entwicklung der menschlichen Gesellschaft. Imago, 1924, Vol. X, p. 278], ''[[The International Journal of Psychoanalysis]]'', Vol. 7, p. 89.</ref> gained her entry to the [[Vienna Psychoanalytical Society]].<ref name=IDP/> \n\nBeata Rank always kept a good personal relationship with Freud. However, her emphasis on the importance of women may well have encouraged Otto Rank's increasing theoretical emphasis on the [[mother-child relationship]], an element in what became his split from Freud.<ref name=\"GeissmannGeissmann2005\"/> Otto started visiting the [[United States]] in 1924, though Beata did not want to move there. After his break from Freud, the couple compromised by moving [[Paris]] in 1926. There she continued researching the role of women, using the [[Bibliotheque Nationale]]. In 1933 she worked with Otto as an adminstrator for the Summer Institute of his Psychological Center, but in 1934 he left her.<ref name=IDP/>\n\nBeata Rank remained in Paris with her daughter until 1936, when they emigrated to [[Boston]]. The Boston psychoanalytic community included her old friends [[Helene Deutsch|Helene]] and [[Felix Deutsch]]. She worked there as a [[child analyst]] and as a training analyst at the [[Boston Psychoanalytic Institute]].<ref name=IDP/>\n\nBeata Rank died on April 11, 1961.<ref name=IDP/>\n\n==Works==\n* 'Zur Rolle der Frau in der Entwicklung der menschlichen Gesellschaft' [On the role of the woman in the development of human society], ''Imago'', Vol. 10 (1924), pp. 278-295.\n* 'Where child analysis stands today', ''[[American Imago]]'', Vol. 3, No. 3 (1942). pp. 41-60.\n*  (with Marion C. Putnam and G. Rochlin) 'The Significance of \"Emotional Climate\" in Early Feeding Difficulties', ''Psychosomatic Medicine'', Vol. 10, No. 5 (1948), pp.279-83\n* 'Adaptation of the psychoanalytic technique for the treatment of young children with atypical development', ''American Journal of Orthopsychiatry'', Vol. 19 (1949), pp. 130-139.\n* 'Aggression', in Phyllis Greenacre et al, eds., ''The psychoanalytic study of the child'', Vol. 3-4 (1949).\n* 'Intensive study and treatment of pre-school children who show marked personality deviations, or atypical development and their parents', in G. Caplan, ed., ''Emotional problems of early childhood: Proceedings of the International Institute of Child Psychiatry'', New York: Basic, pp. 491-501.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rank, Beata}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:American psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''Beata Rank-Minzer''', born '''Beata Minzer''' or '''Munzer''', known to friends by the nickname '''Tola''' (1886 - 1967) was a Polish-American psychoanalyst.<ref name=IDP>Helene Rank-Veltfort, [https://www.encyclopedia.com/psychology/dictionaries-thesauruses-pictures-and-press-releases/rank-minzer-munzer-beata-1886-1961 Rank-Minzer (Munzer), Beata (1886-1961)], ''International Dictionary of Psychoanalysis''. Online at encyclopedia.com. Accessed 28 March 2020.</ref><ref>[[Paul Roazen]], 'Tola Rank', ''Revue internationale d'histoire de la psychanalyse'', 1990.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBeata Minzer was born on February 16, 1886 in [[Neusandetz]] near [[Krakow]], Poland, then part of the [[Austrian-Hungarian Empire]].<ref name=IDP/> Her aunt instroduced her to [[Otto Rank]], who was stationed in Krakow editing the ''Krakauer Zeitung'' from 1916-18. They married in a Jewish wedding ceremony on November 7, 1918, days before the end of [[World War I]]. The couple moved to [[Vienna]] soon afterwards, where Otto took her to present to [[Sigmund Freud]] as a sort of 'court presentation'.<ref name=\"GeissmannGeissmann2005\">{{cite book|author1=Pierre Geissmann|author2=Claudine Geissmann|title=A History of Child Psychoanalysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqyIAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA134|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-83002-2|pages=134\u20137}}</ref> Their only child, Helene, was born in August 1919. \n\nThough Freud's initial impression of Beata Rank had been unfavourable - \"a little Polish-Jewish wife whom no-one finds congenial and who betrays no higher interests\" \u2013 he soon revised his opinion.<ref name=\"Gay1998\">{{cite book|last=Gay|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Gay|title=Freud: A Life for Our Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mZ5eX44E9lYC&pg=PA471|year=1998|publisher=W. W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-07234-1|pages=471\u20132}}</ref>\nShe became [[Freud]]'s hostess for social events, entertaining visitors like [[Lou Andreas-Salom\u00e9]].<ref name=\"Lieberman2010\">{{cite book|author=E. James Lieberman|title=Acts of Will: The Life and Work of Otto Rank|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HWB38ycJxd0C&pg=PA155|year=2010|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4391-1915-0|page=155}}</ref> She attended lectures and seminars on psychoanalysis. Like [[Anna Freud]] \u2013 who felt some rivalry towards her \u2013\u00a0she took dictation from Freud in the publication of ''Imago''.<ref name=\"GeissmannGeissmann2005\"/> In 1923 she translated [[Freud]]'s ''On Dreams'' \u2013 an abridged version of ''[[The Interpretation of Dreams]]'' \u2013\u00a0into Polish. A 1923 paper on the role of women in the development of human society, which integrated Freud's theory of [[Oedipal conflict]] with [[Bachofen]]'s' [[mother-right]] theory,<ref>J. C. F., [https://www.pep-web.org/document.php?id=ijp.007.0089a Applied Psycho-Analysis: Beata Rank. Zur Rolle der Frau in der Entwicklung der menschlichen Gesellschaft. Imago, 1924, Vol. X, p. 278], ''[[The International Journal of Psychoanalysis]]'', Vol. 7, p. 89.</ref> gained her entry to the [[Vienna Psychoanalytical Society]].<ref name=IDP/> \n\nBeata Rank always kept a good personal relationship with Freud. However, her emphasis on the importance of women may well have encouraged Otto Rank's increasing theoretical emphasis on the [[mother-child relationship]], an element in what became his split from Freud.<ref name=\"GeissmannGeissmann2005\"/> Otto started visiting the [[United States]] in 1924, though Beata did not want to move there. After his break from Freud, the couple compromised by moving [[Paris]] in 1926. There she continued researching the role of women, using the [[Bibliotheque Nationale]]. In 1933 she worked with Otto as an adminstrator for the Summer Institute of his Psychological Center, but in 1934 he left her.<ref name=IDP/>\n\nBeata Rank remained in Paris with her daughter until 1936, when they emigrated to [[Boston]]. The Boston psychoanalytic community included her old friends [[Helene Deutsch|Helene]] and [[Felix Deutsch]]. She worked there as a [[child analyst]] and as a training analyst at the [[Boston Psychoanalytic Institute]].<ref name=IDP/>\n\nBeata Rank died on April 11, 1961.<ref name=IDP/>\n\n==Works==\n* 'Zur Rolle der Frau in der Entwicklung der menschlichen Gesellschaft' [On the role of the woman in the development of human society], ''Imago'', Vol. 10 (1924), pp. 278-295.\n* 'Where child analysis stands today', ''[[American Imago]]'', Vol. 3, No. 3 (1942). pp. 41-60.\n*  (with )Marion C. Putnam and G. Rochlin) 'The Significance of \"Emotional Climate\" in Early Feeding Difficulties', ''Psychosomatic Medicine'', Vol. 10, No. 5 (1948), pp.279-83\n* 'Adaptation of the psychoanalytic technique for the treatment of young children with atypical development', ''American Journal of Orthopsychiatry'', Vol. 19 (1949), pp. 130-139.\n* 'Aggression', in Phyllis Greenacre et al, eds., ''The psychoanalytic study of the child'', Vol. 3-4 (1949).\n* 'Intensive study and treatment of pre-school children who show marked personality deviations, or atypical development and their parents', in G. Caplan, ed., ''Emotional problems of early childhood: Proceedings of the International Institute of Child Psychiatry'', New York: Basic, pp. 491-501. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rank, Beata}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:Polish psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:American psychoanalysts]]\n[[Category:Jewish emigrants from Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Dsp13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks:rm  stray punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beata_Rank"}
{"title_page": "Angela Rayner", "text_new": "{{Warning |image=Ambox_current_red.svg |heading=Warning! |This article is being heavily edited because of a recent election. Surrounding events may change rapidly as more facts come. Initial news reports may be unreliable, and the most recent updates to this article may not reflect the most current information. Please feel free to improve this article (but note that updates without valid and reliable references will be removed) or discuss changes on the talk page.}}\n\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Angela Rayner\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image               = Official portrait of Angela Rayner MP crop 2.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Rayner in 2019\n| office              = [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| leader              = [[Keir Starmer|Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start          = 4 April 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]\n| leader1             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]] <br> [[Keir Starmer|Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start1         = 1 July 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Pat Glass]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Shadow Minister for Women and Equalities]]\n| leader2             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2         = 27 June 2016\n| term_end2           = 6 October 2016\n| predecessor2        = [[Kate Green]]\n| successor2          = [[Sarah Champion]]\n| office3             = [[Official Opposition frontbench#Social services|Shadow Minister of State for Pensions]]\n| leader3             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3         = 11 January 2016\n| term_end3           = 1 July 2016\n| predecessor3        = [[Nick Thomas-Symonds]]\n| successor3          = [[Alex Cunningham]]\n| office4             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n| term_start4         = 7 May 2015\n| term_end4           = \n| predecessor4        = [[David Heyes]]\n| successor4          = \n| majority4           = 4,263 (11.1%)\n| birth_name          = Angela Bowen\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|3|28}}\n| birth_place         = [[Stockport]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Mark Rayner|2010}}\n| children            = 3\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Angela Rayner''' (''{{n\u00e9e}}'' '''Bowen'''; born 28 March 1980) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]<nowiki/> since [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]<ref name=\"2015 result\">{{cite news |title=Ashton-under-Lyne |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511133428/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |archivedate=11 May 2015  }}</ref> and [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy leader of the Labour Party]] since 2020.\n\nShe has served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]] since 2016. As Shadow Education Secretary, Rayner has proposed the creation of a [[National Education Service]] (NES), modelled on the [[National Health Service]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|title=Labour to outline plans for National Education Service and 'cradle to grave' learning|date=26 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205404/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nRayner left secondary school aged 16 whilst pregnant and without any qualifications. She later trained as a [[care worker]], eventually becoming a [[union representative|trade union representative]] within [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]], during which time she joined the Labour Party. Shortly after her election to the [[House of Commons]] in 2015, she was described in the media as being part of the Labour Party's [[soft left]]. \n\nIn January 2016, Corbyn appointed Rayner as a [[Shadow Cabinet|Junior Shadow Minister]] for Pensions, and later for Women and Equalities, in June. She has since been considered by some as a possible future [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Leader]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |title=Labour's Angela Rayner: 'I'm proper working-class and Jeremy Kyle' |last=Moss |first=Stephen |date=28 July 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728232408/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |archivedate=28 July 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|title=The irresistible rise of Angela Rayner|website=www.newstatesman.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926230219/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|archivedate=26 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|title=Corbyn says 2 Labour MPs tipped to replace him could 'absolutely' be leaders|first=Todd|last=Fitzgerald|date=10 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108151705/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> However, Rayner opted to not run for the Labour leadership in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]], choosing to support her flat-mate [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and instead successfully [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|stood for Deputy Leader]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRayner was born on 28 March 1980 in [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\">'RAYNER, Angela', ''[[Who's Who 2017]]'', A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016; online edn., November 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U283864 accessed 5 Oct 2017]</ref> She attended [[Stockport Academy|Avondale School]] in Stockport, leaving the school aged 16 after becoming pregnant, and did not obtain any qualifications.<ref name=\"oldham\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |title=Not bad for a ginger kid! |publisher=[[Oldham Chronicle]] |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819045552/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |archivedate=19 August 2016  }}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ Teen mum turned Labour MP: Why Angela Rayner should have the Tories running scared] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930081709/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ |date=30 September 2016 }}, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 29 September 2016</ref> She later studied part-time at [[Stockport College]], learning [[British Sign Language]], and qualifying as a [[Social care|social care worker]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\" />\n\n==Early career==\nAfter leaving college, Rayner worked for [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council]] as a care worker for a number of years. During this time, she was also elected as a trade union representative for [[UNISON|Unison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |title=Joining a trade union |publisher=[[GOV.UK]] |date=15 December 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917171227/https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |archivedate=17 September 2016  }}</ref> She was later elected as [[convenor]] of [[UNISON|Unison]] [[North West England|North West]], becoming the union's most senior official in the region.<ref name=\"schoolsweek\" /><ref name=\"Fitzgerald\">{{cite news|last=Fitzgearld|first=Todd|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|title=Commons vow by new Ashton MP Angela Rayner who was told she'd amount to nothing|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=13 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181523/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' featured a lengthy profile of Rayner in 2012, as part of an article on a trade union officer's working life.<ref>{{cite news|title=A working life: the Union Official|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216161110/https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|archivedate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n[[File:Angela Rayner, 2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election hustings, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright|Rayner speaking at the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] hustings in Bristol]]\nIn 2014, Rayner was selected to become Labour's candidate for the seat of [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]], after the retirement of [[David Heyes]]. She won the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], increasing both the Labour majority and its share of the vote in the constituency.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Labour candidate: We need real people with life experience to bring common sense to Parliament|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=8 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915003947/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref> She delivered her [[maiden speech]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 3 June 2015. In the 2017 general election held on Thursday 8 June 2017, Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat, increasing both the Labour majority and vote share. Rayner held her Ashton-under-Lyne seat a third time after winning the constituency in the general election held on Thursday 12 December 2019.\n\nRayner nominated [[Andy Burnham]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour leadership election]], but the following year became one of just 18 MPs to back the incumbent [[Jeremy Corbyn]] against challenger [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 leadership election]].<ref name=\"KeepCorbyn\">{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|title=Corbyn addresses crowd of up to 10,000 on eve of confidence vote|publisher=[[LabourList]]|last=Pine|first=Sarah|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701080636/http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2016, after a series of resignations from the [[Shadow Cabinet (UK)|Shadow Cabinet]], Corbyn appointed Rayner to the position of [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]].<ref name=\"schoolsweek\">{{cite web |url=http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |title=Exclusive: Angela Rayner becomes third shadow education secretary in a week |publisher=Schools Week |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711090147/http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |archivedate=11 July 2016  }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 UK general election|2019 general election]] Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat being returned as Member of Parliament for the third time in 5 years. She was elected as [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|deputy leader]] on [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|4 April 2020]], replacing [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]].\n\n==Political views==\nIn a 2017 interview discussing her political beliefs, Rayner highlighted her [[pragmatism]], described herself as being part of the \"[[soft left]]\" of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"auto\"/> As shadow education secretary, Rayner has championed the policy of a \u2019National Education Service\u2019, which would be modelled along similar lines to the UK [[National Health Service]], as well as promoting an increase in funding to early years education. She has previously written that decreasing teachers' salaries would lead to shortages in those joining the profession.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 England's schools face 'severe' teacher shortage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114622/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 |date=30 August 2018 }} ''[[BBC News]]''. 20 August 2018''</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, she married Mark Rayner, a Unison official.<ref name=\"WW 2017\" /> She has three sons: Ryan, who was born when she was aged 16; Jimmy; and Charlie.<ref name=\"oldham\" /> Charlie was born prematurely at 23 weeks and Rayner says that the care he received demonstrated the importance of the NHS to her.<ref name=\"Fitzgerald\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=UK unions blast Education Secretary over controversial reforms|url=http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|publisher=Equal Times|date=30 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518065658/http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref> Rayner lives in her constituency of [[Ashton-under-Lyne]] with her family. She became a grandmother in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|title=Grangela: Labour's Angela Rayner is grandmother at 37|date=22 November 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122135913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|archivedate=22 November 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Evan Davis]] of the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] in 2018, Rayner said that her mother had been unable to read or write; a repeat of part of a tribute she made to her mother in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |title=Labour MP Angela Rayner's tribute to her 'inspirational' mother |work=inews.co.uk |date=24 September 2016 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925025945/https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |archive-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Rayner revealed that she had fitted [[panic button]]s at her home after rape and death threats were sent to her a few weeks earlier.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Angela Rayner has panic buttons fitted after online threats |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |accessdate=4 March 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304212645/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |archive-date=4 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, she confirmed she had been suffering symptoms of [[coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] and was self-isolating following medical advice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-03-27/north-west-mp-angela-rayner-says-she-is-self-isolating/|title=North West MP Angela Rayner says she is self-isolating|work=ITV News|date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.angelarayner.com/}}\n*[https://twitter.com/AngelaRayner?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Twitter]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=angela-rayner/4356 |publicwhip=Angela_Rayner |theywork=angela_rayner}}\n* [http://unisonactive.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/proud-loud-and-unison-angie-rayners.html ''UNISON blog'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Heyes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pat Glass]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}{{North West Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rayner, Angela}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n[[Category:People from Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n[[Category:People from Stockport]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Women trade unionists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Warning |image=Ambox_current_red.svg |heading=Warning! |This article is being heavily edited because of a recent election. Surrounding events may change rapidly as more facts come. Initial news reports may be unreliable, and the most recent updates to this article may not reflect the most current information. Please feel free to improve this article (but note that updates without valid and reliable references will be removed) or discuss changes on the talk page.}}\n\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Angela Rayner\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image               = Official portrait of Angela Rayner MP crop 2.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Rayner in 2019\n| office              = [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| leader              = [[Keir Starmer|Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start          = 4 April 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]\n| leader1             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]] <br> [[Keir Starmer|Sir Keir Starmer]]\n| term_start1         = 1 July 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Pat Glass]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Shadow Minister for Women and Equalities]]\n| leader2             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2         = 27 June 2016\n| term_end2           = 6 October 2016\n| predecessor2        = [[Kate Green]]\n| successor2          = [[Sarah Champion]]\n| office3             = [[Official Opposition frontbench#Social services|Shadow Minister of State for Pensions]]\n| leader3             = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start3         = 11 January 2016\n| term_end3           = 1 July 2016\n| predecessor3        = [[Nick Thomas-Symonds]]\n| successor3          = [[Alex Cunningham]]\n| office4             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n| term_start4         = 7 May 2015\n| term_end4           = \n| predecessor4        = [[David Heyes]]\n| successor4          = \n| majority4           = 4,263 (11.1%)\n| birth_name          = Angela Bowen\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|3|28}}\n| birth_place         = [[Stockport]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Mark Rayner|2010}}\n| children            = 3\n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Angela Rayner''' (''{{n\u00e9e}}'' '''Bowen'''; born 28 March 1980) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]<nowiki/> since [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]<ref name=\"2015 result\">{{cite news |title=Ashton-under-Lyne |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511133428/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000537 |archivedate=11 May 2015  }}</ref> and [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Deputy leader of the Labour Party]] since 2020.\n\nShe has served in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]] since 2016. As Shadow Education Secretary, Rayner has proposed the creation of a [[National Education Service]] (NES), modelled on the [[National Health Service]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|title=Labour to outline plans for National Education Service and 'cradle to grave' learning|date=26 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205404/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-party-conference-2017-angela-rayner-national-education-service-jeremy-corbyn-a7967101.html|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nRayner left secondary school aged 16 whilst pregnant and without any qualifications. She later trained as a [[care worker]], eventually becoming a [[union representative|trade union representative]] within [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]], during which time she joined the Labour Party. Shortly after her election to the [[House of Commons]] in 2015, she was described in the media as being part of the Labour Party's [[soft left]]. \n\nIn January 2016, Corbyn appointed Rayner as a [[Shadow Cabinet|Junior Shadow Minister]] for Pensions, and later for Women and Equalities, in June. She has since been considered by some as a possible future [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Leader]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |title=Labour's Angela Rayner: 'I'm proper working-class and Jeremy Kyle' |last=Moss |first=Stephen |date=28 July 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=28 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728232408/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/28/angela-rayner-shadow-education-secretary-interview |archivedate=28 July 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|title=The irresistible rise of Angela Rayner|website=www.newstatesman.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926230219/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/irresistible-rise-angela-rayner|archivedate=26 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|title=Corbyn says 2 Labour MPs tipped to replace him could 'absolutely' be leaders|first=Todd|last=Fitzgerald|date=10 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108151705/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/jeremy-corbyn-says-two-labour-9791157|archivedate=8 November 2017}}</ref> However, Rayner opted to not run for the Labour leadership in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]], choosing to support her flat-mate [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and instead successfully [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|stand for Deputy Leader]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nRayner was born on 28 March 1980 in [[Stockport]], [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\">'RAYNER, Angela', ''[[Who's Who 2017]]'', A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016; online edn., November 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U283864 accessed 5 Oct 2017]</ref> She attended [[Stockport Academy|Avondale School]] in Stockport, leaving the school aged 16 after becoming pregnant, and did not obtain any qualifications.<ref name=\"oldham\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |title=Not bad for a ginger kid! |publisher=[[Oldham Chronicle]] |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819045552/http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/news-features/101/features/88867/not-bad-for-a-ginger-kid |archivedate=19 August 2016  }}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ Teen mum turned Labour MP: Why Angela Rayner should have the Tories running scared] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930081709/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/politics/teen-mum-turned-labour-mp-why-angela-rayner-should-have-the-tori/ |date=30 September 2016 }}, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 29 September 2016</ref> She later studied part-time at [[Stockport College]], learning [[British Sign Language]], and qualifying as a [[Social care|social care worker]].<ref name=\"WW 2017\" />\n\n==Early career==\nAfter leaving college, Rayner worked for [[Stockport Metropolitan Borough Council]] as a care worker for a number of years. During this time, she was also elected as a trade union representative for [[UNISON|Unison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |title=Joining a trade union |publisher=[[GOV.UK]] |date=15 December 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917171227/https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/joining-a-trade-union |archivedate=17 September 2016  }}</ref> She was later elected as [[convenor]] of [[UNISON|Unison]] [[North West England|North West]], becoming the union's most senior official in the region.<ref name=\"schoolsweek\" /><ref name=\"Fitzgerald\">{{cite news|last=Fitzgearld|first=Todd|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|title=Commons vow by new Ashton MP Angela Rayner who was told she'd amount to nothing|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=13 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181523/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/commons-vow-new-ashton-mp-9385503|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' featured a lengthy profile of Rayner in 2012, as part of an article on a trade union officer's working life.<ref>{{cite news|title=A working life: the Union Official|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216161110/https://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/feb/17/working-life-union-official-unison|archivedate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n[[File:Angela Rayner, 2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election hustings, Bristol.jpg|thumb|upright|Rayner speaking at the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] hustings in Bristol]]\nIn 2014, Rayner was selected to become Labour's candidate for the seat of [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]], after the retirement of [[David Heyes]]. She won the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], increasing both the Labour majority and its share of the vote in the constituency.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Labour candidate: We need real people with life experience to bring common sense to Parliament|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]]|date=8 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915003947/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/new-labour-candidate-need-real-7736452|archivedate=15 September 2014}}</ref> She delivered her [[maiden speech]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 3 June 2015. In the 2017 general election held on Thursday 8 June 2017, Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat, increasing both the Labour majority and vote share. Rayner held her Ashton-under-Lyne seat a third time after winning the constituency in the general election held on Thursday 12 December 2019.\n\nRayner nominated [[Andy Burnham]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 Labour leadership election]], but the following year became one of just 18 MPs to back the incumbent [[Jeremy Corbyn]] against challenger [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 leadership election]].<ref name=\"KeepCorbyn\">{{cite web|url=http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|title=Corbyn addresses crowd of up to 10,000 on eve of confidence vote|publisher=[[LabourList]]|last=Pine|first=Sarah|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701080636/http://labourlist.org/2016/06/corbyn-addresses-crowd-of-up-to-10000-on-eve-of-confidence-vote/|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2016, after a series of resignations from the [[Shadow Cabinet (UK)|Shadow Cabinet]], Corbyn appointed Rayner to the position of [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]].<ref name=\"schoolsweek\">{{cite web |url=http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |title=Exclusive: Angela Rayner becomes third shadow education secretary in a week |publisher=Schools Week |date=1 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711090147/http://schoolsweek.co.uk/angela-rayner-becomes-third-shadow-education-secretary-in-a-week/ |archivedate=11 July 2016  }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2019 UK general election|2019 general election]] Rayner successfully defended her Ashton-under-Lyne seat being returned as Member of Parliament for the third time in 5 years. She was elected as [[Deputy leader of the Labour Party (UK)|deputy leader]] on [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|4 April 2020]], replacing [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]].\n\n==Political views==\nIn a 2017 interview discussing her political beliefs, Rayner highlighted her [[pragmatism]], described herself as being part of the \"[[soft left]]\" of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"auto\"/> As shadow education secretary, Rayner has championed the policy of a \u2019National Education Service\u2019, which would be modelled along similar lines to the UK [[National Health Service]], as well as promoting an increase in funding to early years education. She has previously written that decreasing teachers' salaries would lead to shortages in those joining the profession.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 England's schools face 'severe' teacher shortage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114622/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-45341734 |date=30 August 2018 }} ''[[BBC News]]''. 20 August 2018''</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2010, she married Mark Rayner, a Unison official.<ref name=\"WW 2017\" /> She has three sons: Ryan, who was born when she was aged 16; Jimmy; and Charlie.<ref name=\"oldham\" /> Charlie was born prematurely at 23 weeks and Rayner says that the care he received demonstrated the importance of the NHS to her.<ref name=\"Fitzgerald\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=UK unions blast Education Secretary over controversial reforms|url=http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|publisher=Equal Times|date=30 April 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518065658/http://www.equaltimes.org/uk-unions-blast-education-secretary-over-controversial-reforms?lang=en|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref> Rayner lives in her constituency of [[Ashton-under-Lyne]] with her family. She became a grandmother in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|title=Grangela: Labour's Angela Rayner is grandmother at 37|date=22 November 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122135913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42078457|archivedate=22 November 2017|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Evan Davis]] of the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] in 2018, Rayner said that her mother had been unable to read or write; a repeat of part of a tribute she made to her mother in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |title=Labour MP Angela Rayner's tribute to her 'inspirational' mother |work=inews.co.uk |date=24 September 2016 |accessdate=6 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925025945/https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/labour-mp-angela-rayners-tribute-inspirational-mother/ |archive-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Rayner revealed that she had fitted [[panic button]]s at her home after rape and death threats were sent to her a few weeks earlier.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Angela Rayner has panic buttons fitted after online threats |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |accessdate=4 March 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304212645/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/mar/04/angela-rayner-has-panic-buttons-fitted-after-online-threats |archive-date=4 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, she confirmed she had been suffering symptoms of [[coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus disease]] and was self-isolating following medical advice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/granada/2020-03-27/north-west-mp-angela-rayner-says-she-is-self-isolating/|title=North West MP Angela Rayner says she is self-isolating|work=ITV News|date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.angelarayner.com/}}\n*[https://twitter.com/AngelaRayner?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Twitter]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=angela-rayner/4356 |publicwhip=Angela_Rayner |theywork=angela_rayner}}\n* [http://unisonactive.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/proud-loud-and-unison-angie-rayners.html ''UNISON blog'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Heyes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Ashton-under-Lyne (UK Parliament constituency)|Ashton-under-Lyne]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pat Glass]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}{{North West Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rayner, Angela}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n[[Category:People from Ashton-under-Lyne]]\n[[Category:People from Stockport]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Women trade unionists]]\n", "name_user": "GrahamN-UK", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction Clean up/copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angela_Rayner"}
